"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578600","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-13","<p>I meet Cabinet colleagues regularly to discuss a range of issues. My officials in the Government Digital Service work with the Department of Culture, Media &amp; Sport on digital inclusion and engagement. Government is working in partnership with the private and voluntary sectors to ensure that everyone in the UK has the basic digital skills needed to benefit in the digital age. To date, more than 90 organisations, including EE, Vodafone, Age UK, the LGA, Tinder Foundation, Microsoft, Shelter and Google have signed up to the Government’s Digital Inclusion Charter to develop initiatives that reach as many people as possible. We are committed to ensuring every UK citizen who can be online will be by 2020.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578600/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T13:26:40.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578600/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578600/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-08","Digital Technology: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what discussions he has had with his Cabinet colleagues on the rollout of digital infrastructure in rural areas as part of the move to deliver public services through digital technology.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","45597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578601","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-14","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave him on Wednesday 7 September 2016 to UIN: 44500.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578601/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-14T10:07:49.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578601/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578601/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-08","Government Departments: Performance Appraisal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of all government departments adopting the same practice of informal monthly performance reviews which has been implemented by the Valuation Office Agency.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","45587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578602","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-16","<p>The overarching principle behind all public procurement policy is to award contracts on the basis of achieving the best value for money for the taxpayer.</p><p>It is the responsibility of the individual contracting authorities to decide whether, how and when to go to market for the procurement of goods and services.</p><p>Analysis by the Crown Commercial Service shows no significant variation in the number of above threshold opportunities advertised in the Official Journal of the EU. Analysis of opportunities over £10k advertised on Contracts Finder show a drop in the levels of procurement activity prior to the referendum, consistent with deferring advertisements during the Civil Service’s period of “purdah”, rather than a sudden increase in new activity since the referendum.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578602/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T07:56:12.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578602/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578602/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-08","Public Sector: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the reasons for the large increase in public sector contracts going out to tender since the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","45594"
