"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578609","Leader of the House","false","2016-09-13","<p>Bills formally submitted to the Public Bill Office are available to all Members and are published online. Government Departments are holding discussions with several Members about their Bills.<br><br>The Government will set out its position on each Bill at the relevant Second Reading.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578609/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T16:37:17.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578609/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578609/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2016-09-08","Private Members' Bills","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, pursuant to the Answer of 5 September 2016 to Question 43403, what the evidential basis is for his assertion that no hon. Members have handed in the text of their Bill; what discussions he and his officials have had with House authorities on the status of each of the Private Members' Bills presented on 29 June 2016; and which Bills have been received by Parliamentary Counsel in draft as part of the process of discussion with Departments.","false","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker","45752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578610","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-13","<p>A list of special advisers and pay bands will be published in due course.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578610/answer",,,,,"45746","2016-09-13T09:04:27.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578610/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578610/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-08","Cabinet Office: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the pay grade is of each special adviser in his Department.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","45720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578611","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-15","<p>I have responsibility for Policy Innovation Lab. The Policy Lab sits in the Cabinet Office but works for all departments and reports to the Policy Profession Board.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578611/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-15T08:04:19.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578611/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578611/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-08","Policy Lab","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which Minister oversees the Policy Innovation Lab.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","45736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578612","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-15","<p>No new Extended Ministerial Offices have been established since 13 July. We will report in due course in an appropriate Civil Service update on the experience of their operation to date.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578612/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-15T07:50:51.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578612/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578612/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-08","Extended Ministerial Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether any ministerial extended offices have been set up since 13 July 2016.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","45740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578613","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-13","<p>A list of special advisers and pay bands will be published in due course.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578613/answer",,,,,"45720","2016-09-13T09:04:27.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578613/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578613/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-08","Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many special advisers work for the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","45746"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578614","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-13","<p>The Government has made improvements to ballot papers, forms and instructions used by voters at elections and referendums in order to make voting as accessible as possible. This involved public user-testing of the revised voting forms. The Government will consider reports from the Electoral Commission and other organisations on the polls held during 2016 and decide whether any further action is required.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578614/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T07:59:10.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578614/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578614/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-08","Ballot Papers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 18 July 2016 to Question 42682, whether he is taking steps to reduce the number of spoilt ballots in elections.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","45747"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578615","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-15","<p>Further to the question asked by the Hon Member of 7 September 2016, Official Report, Column 321, I would add that my Rt Hon Friend, the Member for Derbyshire Dales, is a Minister of the Crown and a member of the Cabinet. He will attend a number of Cabinet Committees, which will be published in due course, and has duties directly related to the Duchy of Lancaster. The List of Ministerial Responsibilities will also be published in due course. He does not receive a Ministerial salary from public funds. Details of Private Office staff will be accounted for as part of the regular transparency data on gov.uk. The Government publishes on a quarterly basis details of Ministerial visits overseas. All Ministers have access to the Government Car Service for official travel.</p><p>My Rt Hon Friend also serves as the Party Chairman of the Conservative Party. Such arrangements are no different from the likes of Charles Clarke, Ian McCartney and Hazel Blears, all of whom held the posts of Minister Without Portfolio and Labour Party Chair under the last Labour Government.</p><p>I would also observe that under the Thatcher and Major Governments, senior figures such as Norman Tebbit, Kenneth Baker and Chris Patten served as both Chairman of the Conservative Party and Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578615/answer",,,,,"45760 ; 45882 ; 46070","2016-09-15T15:01:48.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578615/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578615/answer","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578615/answer/previousversion/11307","Biography information for Ben Gummer","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-08","Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster: Government Car Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster has access to the Government Car Services.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","45759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578616","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-15","<p>Further to the question asked by the Hon Member of 7 September 2016, Official Report, Column 321, I would add that my Rt Hon Friend, the Member for Derbyshire Dales, is a Minister of the Crown and a member of the Cabinet. He will attend a number of Cabinet Committees, which will be published in due course, and has duties directly related to the Duchy of Lancaster. The List of Ministerial Responsibilities will also be published in due course. He does not receive a Ministerial salary from public funds. Details of Private Office staff will be accounted for as part of the regular transparency data on gov.uk. The Government publishes on a quarterly basis details of Ministerial visits overseas. All Ministers have access to the Government Car Service for official travel.</p><p>My Rt Hon Friend also serves as the Party Chairman of the Conservative Party. Such arrangements are no different from the likes of Charles Clarke, Ian McCartney and Hazel Blears, all of whom held the posts of Minister Without Portfolio and Labour Party Chair under the last Labour Government.</p><p>I would also observe that under the Thatcher and Major Governments, senior figures such as Norman Tebbit, Kenneth Baker and Chris Patten served as both Chairman of the Conservative Party and Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578616/answer",,,,,"45759 ; 45882 ; 46070","2016-09-15T15:01:48.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578616/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578616/answer","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578616/answer/previousversion/11303","Biography information for Ben Gummer","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-08","Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many civil servants are employed for the purposes of working in the Office of the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","45760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578617","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-14","<p>I refer the hon. Member to my answer to him of 5 September 2016 to UIN: 43759.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578617/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-14T10:14:44.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578617/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578617/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-08","Cabinet Office: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 5 September 2016 to Question 43759, how the Propriety and Ethics Team performed on handling correspondence from hon. Members and Peers in 2015.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","45769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578618","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-13","<p>We assume that the Hon Member is referring to the National Asset Register. HM Treasury have no plans to publish a National Asset Register. The decision to stop publication of a National Asset Register was made before the first publication of the Whole of Government Accounts for 2009-10. The latest version of the Whole of Government Accounts for 2014-15 was published on 26 May 2016.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578618/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T14:04:07.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578618/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578618/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-08","Audit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans to publish the next national audit register.","false","Biography information for George Kerevan","East Lothian","George Kerevan","45767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578619","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-15","<p>As of March 2015, HM Treasury had made £800,000 of equity investments and provided £1,175,000 of loan stock to Local Partnerships. Local Partnerships has so far made £675,000 of repayments of loan stock to HM Treasury.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578619/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-15T14:17:25.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578619/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578619/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-08","Local Partnerships: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much (a) capital and (b) revenue expenditure his Department has given to local partnerships to date; and what estimate he has made of the value of his Department's share in its joint ownership.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","45730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578620","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-13","<p>The Government launched the Making Tax Digital consultations on 15 August. The consultations included an initial impact assessment alongside an overview of the potential costs and savings. This initial assessment shows a reduction in businesses’ on-going administrative costs in the medium term; these proposals do not mean four tax returns a year.</p><p>The Government will publish an updated assessment in the Tax Information and Impact Note to be published alongside draft legislation</p><p>These reforms will bring the tax system into the 21<sup>st</sup> Century, contributing to HM Revenue and Customs’ overall target to reduce administrative burdens for business by £400m.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578620/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T16:15:11.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578620/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578620/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-08","Small Businesses: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the implications for small businesses of his Department's plans to introduce quarterly digital tax returns by 2020.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","45742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578621","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-16","<p>The Airports Commission shortlisted three airport expansion schemes, two at Heathrow and one at Gatwick. The Airports Commission considered that all three of the shortlisted schemes were commercially viable and privately financeable.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is carefully considering all the evidence set out, including that on costs and financing, before making a decision on additional runway capacity.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578621/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T11:29:09.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578621/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578621/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-08","London Airports: Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much private funding (a) Heathrow Airport and (b) Gatwick Airport declared to the Government would be invested as part of its expansion plans.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","45722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578622","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-13","<p>The Chancellor will visit constituencies all across the UK in due course. All his visits are recorded in the transparency data published on gov.uk.</p><p> </p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578622/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T13:57:17.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578622/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578622/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-08","Treasury: South Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many times he has visited South Wales in an official capacity since his appointment; and what future plans he has to visit South Wales.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","45655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578623","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-15","<p>The UK is at the forefront of global efforts to tackle unacceptable pay practices in the banking sector and has the toughest regime on pay of any major financial centre.</p><p> </p><p>Firms are now required to have policies in place to defer, reduce, cancel or clawback bonuses in the event that poor performance or misconduct comes to light and the Government expects firms to be proactive in their application of these policies. Used in this way bonuses can be an effective incentive for staff to act in the long term interests of a business.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s efforts have resulted in a restructuring of pay including a significant reduction in cash bonuses, and a better alignment of risk and reward in the financial sector.</p><p> </p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578623/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-15T14:19:08.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578623/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578623/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-08","Financial Institutions: Incentives","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make it his policy to discourage the financial sector from using performance bonuses in his Autumn Statement.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","45589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578624","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-16","<p>It is the responsibility of local authorities to decide how to allocate funding for youth services, according to local need. Individual local authorities would be best placed to advise on any youth centres that are planned for closure in their local area in 2016-17.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578624/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T11:32:21.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578624/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578624/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-08","Youth Centres: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what information her Department holds on the number of youth centres planned for closure in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","45637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578625","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-16","<p>Government does place an existing statutory duty on local authorities through the Education Act 2006 (Section 507B) to secure, as far as is practicable, sufficient services and activities to improve the wellbeing of young people. However, in fulfilling this responsibility government believes that local authorities should be empowered to decide how best to secure services that meet the needs of young people within the budget that is available to them.</p><p> </p><p>Government is committed to ensuring all young people can reach their full potential and has recently announced an £80 million investment in the youth sector that is being delivered through the Youth Investment Fund and the #iwill Fund.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578625/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T11:35:37.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578625/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578625/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-08","Youth Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of making the provision of youth services a statutory duty for councils.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","45636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578626","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-16","<p>It is the responsibility of local authorities to decide how to allocate funding for youth services, according to local need. There is an existing statutory duty on local authorities through Education Act 2006 (Section 507B) to secure, as far as is practicable, sufficient services and activities to improve the wellbeing of young people. Individual local authorities would be best placed to advise on whether there are plans to increase the number of places in youth services in their local area.</p><p> </p><p>Government is committed to ensuring all young people have the best possible start in life. To demonstrate this, it has recently announced an £80million investment in the youth sector that is being delivered through the Youth Investment Fund and the #iwill Fund.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578626/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T11:30:49.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578626/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578626/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-08","Youth Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the implications for her policies and those of local authorities of the findings of the Unison report, A Future at Risk, published in August 2016, on the number of places in youth services that have been lost since 2010; and whether she plans to increase the number of such places.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","45647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578627","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-15","<p>An Order for the conduct of combined authority mayoral elections will be laid before Parliament after the Conference Recess.</p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578627/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-15T13:09:14.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578627/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578627/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-08","Mayors: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he plans to lay draft regulations on the conduct of the regional mayoral elections planned for May 2017.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","45650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578628","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-10-04","<p>The Technical consultation on the implementation of planning changes, published in February 2016, set out our proposals for expanding the approach to improving planning performance in the processing of planning applications. We are considering responses received.</p><p>We want to raise performance, so we are extending the designation regime - which has improved processing time on major planning applications - to minor planning applications.</p><p><br>The attached table shows the performance in time taken to process major and minor planning applications.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578628/answer","Written Question 45586 table.docx","Written Question 45586 table.docx","Planning applications","Planning applications",,"2016-10-04T16:07:46.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578628/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578628/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-08","Planning Permission: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the change in the time taken to process minor planning applications between 2010 and 2015; and if he will make a statement on the reasons for the change.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","45586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578629","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-13","<p>The department does not issue guidance on forecasting business rates.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578629/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T16:37:50.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578629/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578629/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-08","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 8 September 2016 to Question 45035, what guidance he has issued on how specific local authorities should estimate their potential annual proportion increase in yields from business rates in (a) 2019-20, (b) 2020-21 and (c) 2021-22 to facilitate long-term budgeting.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","45757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578630","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-13","<p>Where an area has plans for its governance arrangements to be changed and proposes this to the Secretary of State, it must provide evidence as to how its proposals are likely to result in the provision of better local public services, significant cost savings, greater value for money, stronger and more accountable local leadership, and sustainability in the medium to long term. It is of course open to any body or person to make representations to the Secretary of State either in support of or in opposition to such proposals.</p><p>As we have made clear during discussions with areas, whilst size is an important consideration for areas considering governance changes, there are no maximum or minimum permitted sizes.</p><p>The level of council tax of any new authority is a matter for the local councils concerned. The government will however maintain council tax referendum thresholds at a modest level in order to help keep bills down for hardworking people. This is always the case including in cases of governance change.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578630/answer",,,,,"45756 ; 45771","2016-09-13T16:33:43.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578630/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578630/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-08","Local Government: Population","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what advice his Department has issued on whether there are maximum or minimum permitted size of the population to be served by (a) district councils, (b) unitary councils and (c) combined authorities in England.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","45754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578631","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-13","<p>Where an area has plans for its governance arrangements to be changed and proposes this to the Secretary of State, it must provide evidence as to how its proposals are likely to result in the provision of better local public services, significant cost savings, greater value for money, stronger and more accountable local leadership, and sustainability in the medium to long term. It is of course open to any body or person to make representations to the Secretary of State either in support of or in opposition to such proposals.</p><p>As we have made clear during discussions with areas, whilst size is an important consideration for areas considering governance changes, there are no maximum or minimum permitted sizes.</p><p>The level of council tax of any new authority is a matter for the local councils concerned. The government will however maintain council tax referendum thresholds at a modest level in order to help keep bills down for hardworking people. This is always the case including in cases of governance change.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578631/answer",,,,,"45754 ; 45771","2016-09-13T16:33:42.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578631/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578631/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-08","Unitary Councils: Council Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether statutory safeguards are in place to ensure that new unitary authorities created as a result of councils seeking to abolish themselves in favour of new unitary structures must set the same band D council tax for all households from their inception; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","45756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578632","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-16","<p>The members of the park homes working group set up by the Government in 2015 were:</p><p>1. Peter Aldous MP (Conservative) - Waveney</p><p>2. Steve Brine MP (Conservative) -Winchester</p><p>3. Natascha Engel MP (Labour) - North East Derbyshire</p><p>4. Sonia McColl - Park Homes Justice Campaign</p><p>5. Brian Doick - National Association of Park Home Residents</p><p>6. Alan Savory - Independent Park Homes Advisory Service</p><p>7. Alicia Dunne - The National Caravan Council</p><p>8. Ros Pritchard - British Holiday and Home Parks Association</p><p>9. Paul Holland - South Oxfordshire and the Vale of White Horse District Council</p><p>10.Lisa Osborn - North Somerset District Council</p><p>11.William Tandoh – Department for Communities and Local Government</p><p>12. Annette Brooke* - Former Liberal Democrat MP for Mid Dorset and North Poole</p><p>13 Stephen Lloyd* - Former Liberal Democrat MP for Eastbourne</p><p>14. Andrew Miller* - Former Labour MP for Ellesmere Port and Neston</p><p>*from February – May 2015</p><p>The terms of reference of the group was to identify evidence of poor practice in the park homes sector and investigate how best to raise standards further and tackle abuse. The group concluded its work earlier this year and I will shortly consider its final recommendations.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578632/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T14:03:53.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578632/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578632/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-08","Mobile Homes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the (a) membership and (b) terms of reference are of the Park Homes Working Groups.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","45729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578633","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-13","<p>Information on adult social care and children’s social care by all local authorities in England are published on the Department’s website.</p><p>2014-15: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing-england-2014-to-2015-individual-local-authority-data-outturn" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing-england-2014-to-2015-individual-local-authority-data-outturn<br></a><br>2015-16: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing-england-2015-to-2016-provisional-outturn" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/local-authority-revenue-expenditure-and-financing-england-2015-to-2016-provisional-outturn<br></a><br>Calculation of an overall average spend figure for local authorities in England would not be valid due to the differing types, responsibilities and situations of each local authority.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578633/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T16:37:28.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578633/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578633/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-08","Social Services: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what information his Department holds on much (a) Dorset County Council, (b) Bournemouth Borough Council and (c) Poole Council spent on (i) adult and (ii) community care in (A) 2014-15 and (B) 2015-16; and what the average of such amount was in England in those periods.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","45755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578634","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-13","<p>Where an area has plans for its governance arrangements to be changed and proposes this to the Secretary of State, it must provide evidence as to how its proposals are likely to result in the provision of better local public services, significant cost savings, greater value for money, stronger and more accountable local leadership, and sustainability in the medium to long term. It is of course open to any body or person to make representations to the Secretary of State either in support of or in opposition to such proposals.</p><p>As we have made clear during discussions with areas, whilst size is an important consideration for areas considering governance changes, there are no maximum or minimum permitted sizes.</p><p>The level of council tax of any new authority is a matter for the local councils concerned. The government will however maintain council tax referendum thresholds at a modest level in order to help keep bills down for hardworking people. This is always the case including in cases of governance change.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578634/answer",,,,,"45754 ; 45756","2016-09-13T16:33:43.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578634/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578634/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-08","District Councils","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the oral Answer of 18 July 2016, Official Report, column 542, what evidence district councils who wish to retain their independence and status in a two-tier system need to produce in order to protect that status.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","45771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578635","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-13","<p>During the BBC Charter Review public consultation we have listened to views across a range of issues in relation to the BBC, including Gaelic language broadcasting.</p><p> </p><p>There is a successful partnership between the BBC and MG Alba for the delivery of Gaelic language broadcasting. The White Paper, published in May 2016, sets out the Government's intention to require maintain a commitment to minority language broadcasting through the new Charter.</p><p> </p><p>The level of funding dedicated to BBC ALBA and the number of hours of in-house Gaelic language programming broadcast are matters for the BBC Board to consider when fulfilling this requirement under the new Charter.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578635/answer",,,,,"45668 ; 45669","2016-09-13T11:38:40.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578635/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578635/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-08","BBC Alba","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the role of Gaelic language broadcasting in delivering the BBC's commitment to public service broadcasting.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","45671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578636","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-13","<p>We recognises the important contribution Gaelic language makes to British culture and the creative industries. The Heritage Lottery Fund recently provided £4 million funding to reopen Lews Castle where over 20 community heritage societies have come together to shape the way the story of the Outer Herbrides is celebrated and shared. Interpretation is in Gaelic first with English subtitles throughout the museum.</p><p> </p><p>UK Government and its agencies are committed to working with the Scottish Government to help the creative industries continue to grow in Scotland, through the provision of broadband and mobile infrastructure, fiscal incentives, export promotion, advocacy and facilitation and the provision of official statistics.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578636/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T11:41:50.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578636/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578636/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-08","Scots Gaelic Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the contribution of Scottish Gaelic language to British culture and the creative industries.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","45670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578637","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-13","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that people, particularly the young and vulnerable, are protected from the risk of gambling-related harm. We are keeping the issue of advertising under review to ensure that sufficient protections are in place, and will not hesitate to take further action if necessary.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578637/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T09:40:44.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578637/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578637/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-08","Gambling: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether her Department plans to initiate a further review of gambling advertising to follow up the review by the Industry Group for Responsible Gambling of 2014.","false","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant","45623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578638","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-13","<p>During the BBC Charter Review public consultation we have listened to views across a range of issues in relation to the BBC, including Gaelic language broadcasting.</p><p> </p><p>There is a successful partnership between the BBC and MG Alba for the delivery of Gaelic language broadcasting. The White Paper, published in May 2016, sets out the Government's intention to require maintain a commitment to minority language broadcasting through the new Charter.</p><p> </p><p>The level of funding dedicated to BBC ALBA and the number of hours of in-house Gaelic language programming broadcast are matters for the BBC Board to consider when fulfilling this requirement under the new Charter.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578638/answer",,,,,"45669 ; 45671","2016-09-13T11:38:40.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578638/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578638/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-08","BBC Alba","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if she will make it her policy to include in the BBC Charter a commitment to broadcast a minimum of 10 hours of in-house Gaelic language programming on BBC ALBA each week.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","45668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578639","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-13","<p>During the BBC Charter Review public consultation we have listened to views across a range of issues in relation to the BBC, including Gaelic language broadcasting.</p><p> </p><p>There is a successful partnership between the BBC and MG Alba for the delivery of Gaelic language broadcasting. The White Paper, published in May 2016, sets out the Government's intention to require maintain a commitment to minority language broadcasting through the new Charter.</p><p> </p><p>The level of funding dedicated to BBC ALBA and the number of hours of in-house Gaelic language programming broadcast are matters for the BBC Board to consider when fulfilling this requirement under the new Charter.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578639/answer",,,,,"45668 ; 45671","2016-09-13T11:38:39.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578639/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578639/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-08","BBC Alba","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what her policy is on the future funding of BBC Gaelic language broadcasting.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","45669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578640","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-13","<p>Government continues to support the excellent work of the Lake District National Park Partnership and other stakeholders, which has led to the Lake District becoming the UK's nomination for World Heritage Status in 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Officials will be present to support the partnership during the World Heritage Committee mission to the Lake District, due to take place in October 2016.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578640/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T09:43:06.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578640/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578640/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-09-08","Lake District National Park","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps her Department is taking to support the Lake District National Park Partnership in its bid for status as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","45619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578641","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-13","<p>The Government remains sympathetic to the circumstances of those affected. We are reviewing the position, but need to take account of the wider consequences for other public sector schemes of making retrospective changes.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578641/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T14:58:45.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578641/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578641/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-08","War Widows","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will make it his policy to restore compensation for war widows who remarried between 1973 and 2005.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","45624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578643","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-14","<p>There is no Government policy concerning living accommodation for the Service Police.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578643/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-14T15:39:40.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578643/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578643/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-08","Ministry of Defence Police: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the Government's policy is on members of the Service Police residing in separate living accommodation to other members of the armed forces.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","45627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578644","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-14","<p>The Service Police are already subject to independent oversight by Her Majesty's Inspector of Constabularies and their reports are placed in the public domain. We also remain committed to the introduction of independent oversight of complaints made against the Service Police and work continues in order to identify the most appropriate means of achieving that.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578644/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-14T15:38:25.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578644/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578644/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-08","Ministry of Defence Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans he has to introduce independent oversight of the Service Police.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","45628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578645","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-14","<p>A person who believes they have been a victim of crime may report the matter to the Service or civilian Police, or to their chain of command. Commanding Officers are under a statutory duty to ensure that all allegations which indicate that a service offence may have been committed - including the offences of sexual assault, voyeurism, exposure and sexual activity in a public lavatory - are properly investigated. The Ministry of Defence has undertaken to review the existing provisions whereby Commanding Officers can decide how best to investigate those allegations of sexual offences which do not fall to be automatically referred to the Police. We expect the review to be complete by the end of the year.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578645/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-14T15:39:05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578645/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578645/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-08","Public Lavatories: Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will make an assessment of the effect of the exclusion of sexual assault, voyeurism, exposure and sexual activity in a public lavatory from the schedule of offences that are subject to the mandatory referrals process on the ability of victims to report such acts.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","45645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578646","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-13","<p>As at 1 July 2016, there were 185,310 serving members of the Armed Forces with 57,590 dependent children.</p><p>Individual Service personnel self-declare the number of children they have on the Joint Personnel Administration (JPA) database. For the purposes of this question, a dependent child is defined as any child under the age of 18, as recorded on JPA. Numbers are rounded to the nearest 10. Numbers ending in 5 are rounded to the nearest 20 to avoid systematic bias.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578646/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T14:57:47.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578646/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578646/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-08","Armed Forces: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many serving members of the armed forces have dependent children.","false","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Mrs Anne-Marie Trevelyan","45675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578647","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-13","<p>There are 3,008 serving Armed Forces personnel in receipt of Continuity of Education Allowance for 4,454 children.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578647/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T14:58:10.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578647/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578647/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-08","Armed Forces: Private Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many serving armed forces personnel are in receipt of Continuity of Education Allowance; and in respect of how many children such allowances are allocated.","false","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Mrs Anne-Marie Trevelyan","45700"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578648","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-13","<p>There are around 100 military personnel based in the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia, including at the Defence section within the British Embassy in Riyadh. These personnel provide mentoring and advice to the Saudi Arabian National Guard as part of the British Military Mission to the Saudi Arabian National Guard. Personnel also work on the Saudi Arabia National Guard Communications Project to acquire and support, modern communications capabilities for the Saudi Arabian National Guard and work on the Ministry of Defence (MOD) Saudi Armed Forces Projects, supporting the United Kingdom's commitment to the defence of Saudi Arabia through the supply of modern military aircraft, naval vessels, weapons and associated support services to the Saudi Armed Forces. We have a small number of liaison personnel who work at the Saudi MOD and Operational Centres. We do not discuss specific numbers for reasons of safeguarding operational security.</p><p>There are no UK Armed Forces personnel based in Yemen.</p><p>There are around 195 military personnel based in Oman, including at the Defence section within the British Embassy in Muscat; personnel on Loan Service to the Omani Armed Forces and others on temporary assignments in the region. These numbers change on a daily basis according to the tasks assigned.</p><p>There are seven military personnel permanently assigned to Qatar (three within the Defence Section in the Embassy and four Loan Service officers working in training establishments). There are also a number of temporary personnel who work at Al Udeid airbase but we do not discuss specific numbers for reasons of safeguarding operational security.</p><p>There are six military personnel permanently assigned to the UAE (three within the Defence Section in the Embassy at Abu Dhabi; one within the Defence Section in the Dubai Consulate; and two Loan Service officers working with the UAE Electronic Warfare and Signals departments). There are also a number of temporary personnel at Al Minhad airbase but we do not discuss specific numbers for reasons of safeguarding operational security .</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578648/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T15:15:36.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578648/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578648/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-08","Middle East: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many UK armed forces personnel are stationed in (a) Saudi Arabia, (b) Yemen, (c) Oman, (d) Qatar and (e) UAE.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","45743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578649","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-10-19","<p>No.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578649/answer",,,,,,"2016-10-19T15:10:47.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578649/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578649/answer","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578649/answer/previousversion/12062","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-08","Saudi Arabia: Cluster Munitions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether technical capacity for the launching of cluster munitions was provided with any UK-manufactured (a) aircraft and (b) unmanned aerial device exported to Saudi Arabia in the last 15 years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","45723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578650","Department for Education","false","2016-09-16","<p>This Government is committed to narrowing the gap in attainment between the most disadvantaged children and their peers, including in the early years. We will be investing over £1 billion more per year by 2019-20 to fund our commitments on the early years entitlements – this includes £300 million per year from 2017-18 for a significant increase to the hourly rate paid for the two, three and four year old entitlements.</p><p> </p><p>The 2014-15 Early Years Foundation Stage Profile results tell us that the proportion of children achieving a good level of development continues to increase – 66% in 2015, compared to 60% in 2014 and 52% in 2013. Furthermore, a higher proportion of children eligible for free school meals are achieving a good level of development – 51% in 2015 compared to 45% in 2014.</p><p> </p><p>We need to continue this improvement. This is why we propose an additional needs factor in our new early years national funding formula, in order to channel funding towards local authorities with a higher relative proportion of children with additional needs. Our consultation on early years funding reform is currently open, and I would encourage my Honourable Friend and his constituents to submit their views.</p><p> </p><p>The Government already provides additional funding for the most disadvantaged three- and four-year olds through the Early Years Pupil Premium. This will continue as a separate funding stream, additional to the early years national funding formula.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578650/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T11:29:05.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578650/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578650/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-09-08","Pre-school Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how she plans to ensure that the forthcoming review of fair funding for early years education will include measures to help close the attainment gap at age five.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","45680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578651","Department for Education","false","2016-09-21","<p>Schools self-select their own admissions category on Edubase. 120 schools are identified as ‘secondary modern’.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not yet hold the income and expenditure data from 2015-16. The data will be available for those which are maintained by the local authority in December 2016, and for those which are academies in the summer of 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The overall expenditure per pupil in secondary modern schools by each region for 2014-15 is listed in the following table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Region</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of secondary modern schools</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Expenditure per pupil (£)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Midlands</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>6,388</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East of England</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>5,738</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>6,228</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North West</p></td><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>6,416</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South East</p></td><td><p>54</p></td><td><p>5,703</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South West</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>5,928</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>West Midlands</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>5,547</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Yorkshire and the Humber</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>6,729</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>England Total</strong></p></td><td><p>117*</p></td><td><p>5,921</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>*Note: There are 3 secondary modern schools for which we do not have comparable financial data for them for this period. One of these converted to an academy during 2014-15, and one was reported as part of a federation with another school. The remaining school did not submit data to the Department. The expenditure per pupil takes into account expenditure from all income sources, including self-generated income.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578651/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-21T16:44:08.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578651/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578651/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-09-08","Secondary Education: Per Capita Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the average annual spend per pupil in secondary modern schools was in 2015-16 in (a) England and (b) each region.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","45762"
