"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578739","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-13","<p>The annual pension entitlements for the current Prime Minister, Chancellor of the Exchequer, Foreign Secretary and Home Secretary are set out in a House of Commons Library briefing note available at <a href="http://researchbriefings.files.parliament.uk/documents/SN04586/SN04586.pdf" target="_blank">http://researchbriefings.files.parliament.uk/documents/SN04586/SN04586.pdf</a></p><p>In 2014/15 the Parliamentary Contributory Pension Fund (PCPF) paid out nearly £22m in pension benefits to former MPs and Ministers and their survivors. Further detail can be found in the PCPF Annual Review 2015, available on the PCPF website at <a href="https://www.mypcpfpension.co.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.mypcpfpension.co.uk/</a>.</p><p>The pensions paid to former Prime Ministers and Speakers come from the Consolidated Fund. In 2015/16 a total of £257,000 was paid to former political office holders or surviving dependents from the Consolidated Fund. Details of these pension payments are in the Consolidated Fund accounts, available at</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/535314/consolidated_funds_web.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/535314/consolidated_funds_web.pdf</a></p><p>Prior to the Public Service Pension Act 2013 holders of the Great Offices of State (Prime Minister, Lord Chancellor and Speaker) participated in separate pension arrangements. Future holders (including the current Prime Minister and Lord Chancellor) of these offices will participate in the Ministerial pension scheme.</p><p>Recent Prime Ministers and Lord Chancellors have chosen to waive some of their pension entitlement and only draw an amount equal to what they would have received if they had been a member of the Ministerial pension scheme.</p><p>Historic information covering payments from these funds can be found online in PCPF Annual Reviews and Consolidated Fund accounts.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578739/answer",,,,,"45684 ; 45685 ; 45687","2016-09-13T08:55:18.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578739/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578739/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-09-08","Ministers: Annuities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will list the (a) current recipients of annuities from ministerial pensions and (b) value in each case of the annuity.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","45686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578740","Prime Minister","false","2016-09-15","The Government is committed to supporting the Greater Manchester events industry, including through VisitBritain, the Government’s Events Industry Board and our £1 million Events Support Programme. I regularly hold discussions with Ministerial colleagues on how we can best support growth in regions across the UK.<p> </p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578740/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-15T08:40:14.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578740/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578740/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-09-08","World Expo: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, whether she has held discussions with Ministerial colleagues on Manchester's bid to host the 2025 World Expo.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","45585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578741","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-13","<p>As a result of the replan exercise by Sir Peter Hendy, resources were redeployed to other projects within Network Rail. The Government is investing £40bn in the railways between 2014-19, which will be a significant boost to the rail supply chain.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578741/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T15:34:36.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578741/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578741/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-08","Railways: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the number of job losses in the rail supply chain in connection with his Department's decisions to pause and unpause the electrification of Midland Mainline and the North TransPennine Route; and what assessment he has made of the number of such job losses as a consequence of Hendy Review rescoping exercise of Control Period 5.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","45604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578742","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-13","<p>No decisions have been taken yet with regard to specifying new rolling stock. However, as part of the competition there will be a public consultation in advance of finalising the Invitation to Tender that will inform any such decision.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578742/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T15:38:05.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578742/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578742/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-08","Rolling Stock: East Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make it his policy to require the ordering of new Intercity bimodal rolling stock as a condition of the next East Midlands rail franchise.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","45605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578743","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-13","<p>Network Rail has estimated between £29.5-£39.5m costs of the pause/un-pause of electrification.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Funding has been provisionally allocated from the Passenger Journey Improvement Time Fund (PJIF) to various schemes, including the Midland Main Line Programme. Subject to affordability and value for money, the allocated funds will be confirmed once schemes have completed the detailed design stage.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the Hendy Review £90million was provisionally allocated to the MML from the PJIF fund for Control Period 5 of which:</p><p> </p><p>Derby to Sheffield PJIF- £49.2m</p><p>Market Harborough PJIF - £27m (This denotes the PJIF element of funding for Market Harborough not the total cost of the scheme)</p><p>Leicester South PJIF - £8m</p><p>(2012/13 prices)</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578743/answer",,,,,"45750","2016-09-13T16:07:45.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578743/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578743/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-08","Midland Main Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Answer of 16 October 2015 to Question 11754, whether Network Rail has estimated the cost to the public purse of the decision to unpause electrification of the Midland Mainline.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","45662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578744","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-15","<p>The Transport Systems Catapult will publish the report within the next month.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578744/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-15T10:01:53.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578744/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578744/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-08","Transport: Skilled Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when the Transport Systems Catapult plans to publish its report on current and future skills for the intelligent mobility sector.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","45691"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578745","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-16","<p>Automated vehicles offer many potential benefits including improved safety, network efficiency, and mobility. There is also a significant industrial prize that the UK is well positioned to take advantage of. There are many potential routes for these technologies to come to market. Fully automated taxis are one such application of the technology. At this stage there are no plans to specify the route to market.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578745/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T11:12:44.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578745/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578745/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-08","Driverless Vehicles: Taxis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what his policy is on the development of fully autonomous taxis.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","45692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578746","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-15","<p>The Department will publish a response to UK Testing Ecosystem for Connected and Autonomous Vehicles: Call for Evidence in the next few months.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578746/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-15T09:57:10.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578746/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578746/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-08","Driverless Vehicles: Testing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when his Department plans to publish its response to the call for evidence on driverless vehicle testing facilities which closed in July 2016.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","45693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578747","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-16","<p>The Centre for Connected and Autonomous Vehicles is currently engaged in the second phase of a joint project with the British Standards Institute and the Transport Systems Catapult to map current standards, identify gaps, and determine how best to utilise standards in support of UK industry. This work encompasses vehicle connectivity such as short-range vehicle-to-vehicle and vehicle-to-infrastructure communication and will report early next year.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578747/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T10:48:59.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578747/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578747/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-08","Motor Vehicles: Telecommunications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what research his Department is undertaking on standards for short-range vehicle-to-vehicle and vehicle-to-infrastructure communication.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","45690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578748","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-13","<p>We hope to publish a Government Response to the consultation on the draft Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy, alongside the final Strategy, once the Government completes its analysis of responses to the consultation and all considerations have been taken into account.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578748/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T09:23:37.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578748/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578748/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-08","Cycling and Walking: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects to respond to his Department's consultation on the draft cycling and walking investment strategy, published in March 2016.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","45656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578749","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-16","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) deals with more than 600,000 medical driver licensing applications annually. The length of time taken to deal with an application depends on the medical condition and whether further information is required from medical professionals.</p><p> </p><p>Between April 2016 and the end of August 2016, the average time taken for a licensing decision to be made was 38 working days. The average time for the period April 2015 to March 2016 was 53 working days.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578749/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T12:08:39.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578749/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578749/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-08","Driving: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the average processing time is for claims for the return of driving licences withdrawn on medical grounds; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","New Forest West","Sir Desmond Swayne","45649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578750","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-16","<p>Highways England is on track to meet its target of mitigating at least 1,150 Noise Important Areas (NIA) by the end of this first Road Period as stated in Highways England’s annual report, published August 2016. It is currently planned that the majority of NIA’s will be mitigated in the latter part of Roads Period 1.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578750/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T11:44:08.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578750/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578750/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-08","Roads: Noise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to page 12 of Highways England's annual report, published in August 2016, whether Highways England is on track to meet its target of mitigating at least 1,150 noise important areas by 2020.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","45682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578751","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-13","<p>The Department does not hold train-level performance information. Both Network Rail and relevant train operators provide comprehensive data and reports to the Department, but punctuality of individual trains is an operational matter for the industry to manage.</p><p> </p><p>The Rail Delivery Group has recently launched a new online tool which enables customers to track the punctuality and reliability record of any train on the national network over a period of up to a year, which can be found at: <a href="http://www.mytrainjourney.co.uk/" target="_blank">http://www.mytrainjourney.co.uk/</a> .</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578751/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T15:42:34.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578751/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578751/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-08","Thameslink Railway Line: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will provide performance data for each month from January 2015 to August 2016 for the Thameslink (a) 0657 Brighton to Bedford, (b) 0722 Brighton to Bedford, (c) 0748 Brighton to Bedford, (d) 0800 Brighton to Bedford, (e) 1550 Bedford to Brighton, (f) 1608 Bedford to Brighton, (g) 1626 Bedford to Brighton and (h) 1708 Bedford to Brighton service.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","45658"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578752","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-16","<p>The Government regulates the existence and price of certain rail fares. We protect passengers by setting the maximum amount regulated fares can increase year-on-year. In general the fares that are regulated include commuter fares (in major cities), some weekly, monthly or annual season tickets, day singles and returns (Oyster Pay As You Go in London) as well as some protected fares like long-distance off-peak return fares (formerly Saver Returns). We have capped the rail fares we regulate at inflation (Retail Price Index) for four years running, and will continue to do so for the life of this parliament. This means those fares we regulate will rise by no more than 1.9% in 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Other fares are unregulated, and train operators are permitted to set these on a commercial basis, taking account of competition from other transport modes and the need to attract business in order to grow their revenue. Unregulated fares include the lower cost Advance purchase fares which have been introduced by a number of operators. This has helped to make some leisure travel services significantly cheaper for passengers who are able to book ahead and commit themselves to travelling on a specific departure, and has also helped to fill emptier trains. While there is a wide range of fares available advance fares are a key rail success of recent years where we have seen huge growth. Unregulated advance tickets have increased from 8% of revenue in 2007/08 to 14% of revenue in 2015/16.</p><p> </p><p>The fares that passengers pay are supporting the biggest modernisation programme on Britain’s railways for over a century. In the five years to 2019, Network Rail is spending more than £38 billion to maintain and improve the network.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578752/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T10:57:16.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578752/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578752/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-08","Railways: Fares","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent representations he has made to rail franchises on above inflation rail increases.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","45695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578753","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-16","<p>The Highways England initiative to deploy a better asset system is being delivered under a programme termed the Integrated Asset Management Information System (IAMIS) in accordance with their Asset Management Strategy. This is being delivered as a rolling programme of development and delivery that is enhancing Highways England’s capability over time.</p><p> </p><p>The programme has already seen the delivery of a number of core maintenance management modules in seven of Highways England’s twelve regions, as well as a foundation national network model that was delivered in March 2016. The remaining parts of the system are currently in development and will be tested and brought on line incrementally, with the latest forecast showing programme completion during the financial year 2019/20.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578753/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T11:17:02.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578753/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578753/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-08","Highways England: Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to page 21 of the Annual Report and Accounts of Highways England, published in August 2016, HC 529, what forecast he has made of when the better asset data system will be fully tested and brought online.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","45703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578754","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-16","<p>Departmental Ministers meet representatives of the haulage industry on a regular basis to discuss issues affecting the sector including the driver shortage. In response to these discussions the government has taken action to increase the supply of vocational driving tests, improved processing times for licences and discussed the availability of facilities for drivers.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, Ministerial colleagues have met industry representatives to discuss the development and funding of apprenticeships and providing targeted support for jobseekers.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578754/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T11:07:28.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578754/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578754/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-08","Large Goods Vehicle Drivers: Vacancies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with representatives of the haulage industry on the reported shortage of HGV drivers.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","45714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578755","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-16","<p>Our global connections are crucial for British business and benefit the whole country. The economic benefits to the UK as a whole, not just London and the South East, will be taken into consideration when making a decision on a preferred scheme for airport expansion, alongside a range of other relevant evidence.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578755/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T10:49:24.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578755/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578755/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-08","London Airports: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of airport expansion at (a) Heathrow and (b) Gatwick Airport on job creation in Yorkshire and the Humber.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","45738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578756","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-13","<p>Network Rail has estimated between £29.5-£39.5m costs of the pause/un-pause of electrification.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Funding has been provisionally allocated from the Passenger Journey Improvement Time Fund (PJIF) to various schemes, including the Midland Main Line Programme. Subject to affordability and value for money, the allocated funds will be confirmed once schemes have completed the detailed design stage.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the Hendy Review £90million was provisionally allocated to the MML from the PJIF fund for Control Period 5 of which:</p><p> </p><p>Derby to Sheffield PJIF- £49.2m</p><p>Market Harborough PJIF - £27m (This denotes the PJIF element of funding for Market Harborough not the total cost of the scheme)</p><p>Leicester South PJIF - £8m</p><p>(2012/13 prices)</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578756/answer",,,,,"45662","2016-09-13T16:07:45.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578756/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578756/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-08","Midland Main Railway Line: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 7 July 2015 to Question 4429, on the Midland Main Line, for what works on which sites on the Midland Main Line for funding under the Passenger Journey Time Fund had been authorised; and what funding has been awarded to date to which of those works under the Passenger Journey Time Fund.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","45750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578757","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-14","<p>Tier 2, the skilled worker visa category for non-EEA nationals, is reserved for graduate level occupations. There are no plans to include HGV drivers in this category.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578757/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-14T15:23:38.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578757/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578757/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-08","Large Goods Vehicle Drivers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to include HGV drivers in the skilled workers category.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","45718"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578758","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-16","<p>No such assessment has been made.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578758/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T10:48:00.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578758/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578758/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-08","Leeds-Bradford Airport: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effect of the lack of a direct route between Leeds Bradford Airport and Heathrow Airport on Yorkshire's economy until that link was restored in 2012.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","45733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578759","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-16","<p>It is estimated that fewer than 10,000 passengers flew between Leeds Bradford airport and the countries listed via Heathrow in 2015.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578759/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T11:19:01.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578759/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/578759/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-08","Leeds-Bradford Airport: BRIC Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many passengers from Leeds Bradford Airport travelled to (a) Brazil, (b) Russia, (c) India and (d) China via Heathrow Airport in 2015.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","45737"
