"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577489","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-12","<p>The most recent publication of the Army List was published in accordance with processes in place at the time, which included officers below the rank of Brigadier.</p><p>The security of our people is our foremost concern and we keep the range of measures we have to address the threats to them under constant review. A revised policy was introduced in November 2015 restricting publications of such lists to senior officers, already considered in the public eye. The Army List 2016 will be published in accordance with the revised policy. The previous Service Lists published on the Gov.UK website have now been removed</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577489/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-12T14:56:48.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577489/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577489/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-09-07","Army: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the most recent version of The Army List has been published in error on his Department's website; whether that list includes details of service personnel ranking below one-star level; and what steps he is taking to improve the online security of personal details of serving members of the armed forces.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","45387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577490","Department for Education","false","2016-09-15","<p>The post 16 area reviews are aimed at improving the quality and relevance of the teaching offer to learners as well as ensuring the long term financial viability of colleges. The reviews take account of the best available evidence including the demand for numeracy and literacy in the local area. 22 area reviews are underway and there is no evidence that access to learning, including access to adult education classes on numeracy and literacy, is being reduced as a result of the area reviews.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577490/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-15T17:28:48.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577490/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577490/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-09-07","Basic Skills","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if the Government will ensure that the current number of places in adult education classes on numeracy and literacy will be maintained following the projected merging of further education institutions.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","45391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577491","Department for International Trade","false","2016-09-14","<p>The UK remains a great place to do business. Annual figures published by the Department for International Trade in August 2016 confirm that the UK remains the number one investment destination in Europe; and the top European destination for investment from emerging markets. The figures show that Britain has benefitted from record-breaking inward investment by foreign companies. Across the country, 2,213 inward investment projects were secured in 2015 to 2016, an 11% increase on the previous year.</p><p>With our world-class research base, a highly skilled workforce, world-leading scientific capabilities and a competitive tax environment that includes R&amp;D tax credits and Patent Box, we are determined that the UK should remain the best place in Europe to innovate, locate and grow a business. The UK is a global leader in science and innovation, winning 13 science Nobel Prizes since 2000 and with more Nobel Prizes per capita than US, France, Germany, Russia or Japan; it is ranked third in the Global Innovation Index and is home to 3 of the world’s top 10 universities. Following the vote to leave the EU, we remain determined to maintain the global competitiveness of the UK research base and business environment. To maintain confidence in the UK’s participation in EU funded research collaborations, the Government announced on 13th August, that HM Treasury will underwrite, for the life of the project, all competitively won EU research funding applied for before our departure from the EU.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577491/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-14T14:12:31.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577491/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577491/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-09-07","Research: Facilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps he is taking to help ensure that research facilities owned by companies whose headquarters are in other EU member states or which are based in such states remain in the UK.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","45382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577492","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-16","<p>UK membership of COST is independent from European Union membership and does not form part of the negotiations to leave the EU. COST is an intergovernmental framework with 36 member countries, including Iceland, Turkey and other countries that are not European Union member states. Our future membership of COST will be decided on the basis of its continuing value to the UK.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577492/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T14:00:24.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577492/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577492/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-07","COST","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will discuss with Cabinet colleagues prioritising the UK's continuing membership of and participation in the COST network in negotiations to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","45383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577493","Department of Health","false","2016-09-12","<p>The National Health Service does not collect data on the number of children of pre-school age who have been diagnosed with Autistic Spectrum Disorder.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577493/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-12T13:14:58.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577493/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577493/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-07","Children: Autism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many diagnoses there have been of autism among pre-school children in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","45341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577494","Department for Education","false","2016-09-15","<p>The Department has a role in monitoring the performance of Multi-Academy Trusts (MATs) and the academies within them. This includes transferring an academy from one MAT to another where there are significant concerns about performance and the MAT does not have the necessary capacity to make improvements.</p><p> </p><p>MATs are charitable trusts and companies limited by guarantee. It is for its board to decide whether or not to dissolve the trust; the Department has no role.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577494/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-15T16:57:08.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577494/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577494/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-09-07","Academies: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many multi-academy trusts her Department has closed in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","45570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577495","Department for Education","false","2016-09-15","<p>The Department’s centralised records do not hold data on who approved or declined the converter academy application as Regional Schools Commissioners (RSCs) act on behalf of the Secretary of State for Education. Therefore only the decision made is recorded in centralised records.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577495/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-15T16:55:49.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577495/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577495/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-09-07","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 5 September 2016 to Question 43735, how many decisions to approve or decline applications from maintained schools to convert to academy status were made by Ministers of her Department in 2015.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","45512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577496","Department for Education","false","2016-09-12","<p>All inadequate academies are automatically subject to scrutiny and close monitoring by Regional Schools Commissioners (RSCs) to secure rapid improvements.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Academic Year</p></td><td><p>*Number of ‘inadequate academies’</p></td><td><p>Number of ‘inadequate academies’ that have moved trusts</p></td><td><p>**Number of ‘inadequate academies that have been issued with a formal notice.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>27</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>45</p></td><td><p>17</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>94</p></td><td><p>33</p></td><td><p>19</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>92</p></td><td><p>24</p></td><td><p>20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>60</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>*The information shown includes those academies inspected within an academic year and therefore if an academy has had more than one inadequate inspection this will be included in each year</p><p>**Excludes formal notices where the academy has since moved trust</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577496/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-12T16:40:30.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577496/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577496/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-09-07","Academies: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many academies judged inadequate had their funding agreement terminated and were closed in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","45537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577497","Department for Education","false","2016-09-15","<p>The Government does not hold this information. It is not possible to predict the exact level of participation in the programme in 2016-17. However, in 2015-16 there were 104 participants in the Executive Educators programme run by Future Leaders Trust.</p><p>This is only one example of this type of course and there are others. For example, UCL Institute of Education and Alliance Manchester Business School (University of Manchester) both run courses for existing and aspiring multi-academy trust CEOs and senior leaders.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577497/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-15T16:54:09.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577497/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577497/answer","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577497/answer/previousversion/11071","Biography information for Edward Timpson","60","Education","Education","2016-09-07","Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 25 July 2016 to Question 43274, what estimate she has made of how many people will attend an Executive Educators programme for multi-academy trust leaders in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","45534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577499","Department for Education","false","2016-09-16","<p>The Department does not keep records of whether its employees are citizens of other EU countries. Departmental staff includes Executive Agencies, but excludes Non-Departmental Public Bodies and all non-payroll staff as this information is not held centrally.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577499/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T13:32:58.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577499/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577499/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-09-07","Department for Education: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many citizens of other EU countries work in her Department, its agencies and non-departmental public bodies.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","45508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577500","Department for Education","false","2016-09-14","<p>The Chief Executive of the Education Funding Agency has a permanent contract of employment, i.e. there is no set end date and the contract will continue until either party decides to end it.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577500/answer",,,,,"45211","2016-09-14T17:00:04.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577500/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577500/answer","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577500/answer/previousversion/11073","Biography information for Edward Timpson","60","Education","Education","2016-09-07","Education Funding Agency: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when the contract of employment of the Chief Executive of the Education Funding Agency is due to expire.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","45452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577501","Department for Education","false","2016-09-15","<p>We are committed to building a society where transgender people feel safe and supported. While individual schools are best placed to decide what pastoral support to put in place, they do this in the framework set by the public sector equality duty.</p><p> </p><p>The provisions of the duty are not intended to be burdensome but set some clear expectations. The Department’s guidance on how the duty applies to schools can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/equality-act-2010-advice-for-schools" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/equality-act-2010-advice-for-schools</a>.</p><p> </p><p>It sets out that the duty includes having due regard to the need to advance equality of opportunity for pupils with protected characteristics – including those who identify as transgender – and schools have to publish information on how they are complying.</p><p> </p><p>The guidance also sets out that advancing equality of opportunity involves, in particular:</p><p>(a) removing or minimising disadvantages suffered by people which are connected to a particular characteristic they have;</p><p>(b) taking steps to meet the particular needs of people who have a particular characteristic; and</p><p>(c) encouraging people who have a particular characteristic to participate fully in any activities.</p><p> </p><p>To further support LGB&amp;T pupils we recently announced £4.4 million in funding over the next two years to support anti-bullying schemes. This includes £2.8 million for six projects tackling homophobic, transphobic and biphobic (HBT) bullying. Bullying is best tackled as part of a whole-school approach to create inclusive environments where pupils get appropriate support and the HBT-focused projects will support schools with doing that.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577501/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-15T17:11:32.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577501/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577501/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-09-07","Pupils: Gender Recognition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that appropriate pastoral and other support is available in schools for people who identify as transgender.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","45468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577502","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-09-12","<p>The criteria Natural England uses when assessing applications for licences for the purpose of preventing the spread of bovine tuberculosis under section 10(2)(a) of the Protection of Badgers Act 1992 can be found on the gov.uk website at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/guidance-to-natural-england-preventing-spread-of-bovine-tb" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/guidance-to-natural-england-preventing-spread-of-bovine-tb</a></p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577502/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-12T14:15:13.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577502/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577502/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-09-07","Bovine Tuberculosis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what criteria her Department used to make the decision on new licenses for badger culling in Cornwall, Herefordshire, Devon, Gloucestershire, Somerset and Dorset.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","45471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577503","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-09-14","<p>Defra is currently assessing our financial requirements for preparing to exit the European Union and once these have been identified we will be reviewing our budgets.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577503/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-14T12:07:00.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577503/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577503/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-09-07","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans she has to amend her Department's budget to meet additional workload arising from preparation for leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","45464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577504","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-09-13","<p>Rewilding techniques, such as woodland creation, leaky debris dams and peatbog restoration can have an impact in slowing the flow of flood water downstream. The Government’s natural flood management demonstration projects, including those at Pickering in Yorkshire and Holnicote in Somerset, have demonstrated that these types of measures can be effective in helping to manage flood risk at a catchment scale, slowing the flow of water and reducing local impacts when carefully incorporated into a wider suite of catchment measures</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government’s long term plan for the environment will look at how to deliver benefits across wider landscapes and whole water catchment areas through more integrated catchment management. Incorporating natural flood management measures is at the heart of this.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577504/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T13:43:01.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577504/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577504/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-09-07","Flood Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment her Department has made of the potential of rewilding to reduce the risk of flooding in the UK.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","45440"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577505","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-09-16","<p>The Government supports setting EU Total Allowable Catches (TACs) at Maximum Sustainable Yield (MSY) in 2017 wherever possible. In accordance with the provisions of Council Regulation 1380 / 2013 a delay in reaching MSY beyond 2017 would be allowed if a proposed TAC reduction would seriously jeopardise the social and economic sustainability of the fishing fleets involved. A decision may also be taken by the Council not to do so if it would merely increase the discarding of fish especially in a mixed fishery.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577505/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T13:48:05.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577505/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577505/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-09-07","Fisheries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Written Statement of 14 July 2016, HCWS89, on the June Agriculture and Fisheries Council, in what cases exceptions should be made to reaching Maximum Sustainable Yield targets.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","45492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577506","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-09-15","<p>Animal health is a devolved policy matter. My department liaises closely with all three devolved administrations, including Northern Ireland, on matters of common interest. It is important that all four administrations can learn from our collective experiences and we have effective arrangements in place to make sure that happens.</p><p>In June 2015, the European Commission’s Food and Veterinary Office carried out an audit of the bovine tuberculosis eradication programme in Northern Ireland, a report of which is available at:</p><p><a href="http://ec.europa.eu/food/audits-analysis/audit_reports/details.cfm?rep_id=3560" target="_blank">http://ec.europa.eu/food/audits-analysis/audit_reports/details.cfm?rep_id=3560</a>.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577506/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-15T10:10:11.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577506/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577506/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-09-07","Bovine Tuberculosis: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment her Department has made of the lessons to be learned from the policies undertaken by the Department for Agriculture, Environment and Rural Affairs in Northern Ireland in relation to the control of the spread of Bovine TB in cattle; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","45489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577507","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-09-13","<p>The marine licence application has yet to be determined, but archaeological interests, including the need for any survey, will be considered as part of the Marine Management Organisation’s decision making.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577507/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T13:50:21.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577507/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577507/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-09-07","Ports: Plymouth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when the archaeological survey for Sutton Harbour in Plymouth will be allowed to commence.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","45555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577508","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-09-13","<p>The application for the proposed boardwalk development is currently on hold until further information is provided by the applicant, which is necessary to continue assessing the application to make a determination. The Marine Management Organisation continues to work with the applicant to ensure issues can be resolved in a timely manner, in addition to having sufficient information to allow a full assessment of any impact on the environment prior to determining the licence.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577508/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T13:46:52.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577508/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577508/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-09-07","Ports: Plymouth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the reasons are for the time taken by the Marine Management Organisation to process the licence application for the boardwalk development at Sutton Harbour in Plymouth.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","45554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577509","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Government works with African governments on the conservation of endangered species through a number of fora. We work multi-laterally through the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES) to protect a wide range of endangered species in Africa. This includes attending the CITES Conference of Parties, the next of which will take place in South Africa between 24 September and 5 October this year, where proposals on a wide range of endangered species of interest to African governments will be discussed. As preparation for this meeting the UK part funded a meeting bringing together African lion range countries to discuss lion conservation in Entebbe during the summer.</p><p>In addition the UK has undertaken bi-lateral work with various African countries, in particular to address illegal wildlife trade since the London Conference on Combatting Illegal Wildlife Trade was held in 2014. This work is supported with £13 million, most of which is distributed through the competitive Illegal Wildlife Trade Challenge Fund.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577509/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-12T14:22:26.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577509/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577509/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-09-07","Nature Conservation: Africa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what work the Government has undertaken with African governments on identifying and protecting endangered species.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","45338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577510","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-09-15","<p>Defra is undertaking detailed planning on our capacity and capability to develop and deliver as a result of the referendum decision. So far this has focused on assessing the immediate needs of our policy and strategy functions and we have launched targeted recruitment across the Civil Service.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577510/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-15T10:06:33.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577510/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577510/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-09-07","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans she has to recruit additional staff to meet the additional workload arising from preparations to leave the EU and the development of new arrangements for a system of post-Common Agricultural Policy farm support.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","45399"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577511","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>We issued a statement on 22 June, expressing concern that the nationality of Bahraini Shia cleric Sheikh Isa Qassim is being revoked. We have raised our concerns at senior levels in the Bahraini government and continue to strongly encourage Bahrain to live up to its international human rights obligations. An official from our Embassy in Bahrain has attended both of his hearings so far. I understand that his next hearing will be on 15 September. We will continue to follow his case closely.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577511/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-12T13:56:21.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577511/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577511/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-07","Sheikh Isa Qassim","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his counterparts in Bahrain on the decision to revoke Sheikh Isa Qassim's Bahraini citizenship.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","45395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577512","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-14","<p>It is vital that the international community is relentless in its efforts to ensure Daesh and its affiliates are defeated wherever they arise, including tackling those fighters who may be retreating from Libya. We are coordinating closely with Egypt and Tunisia to share expertise on border security. More broadly, the UK is playing a leading role in the Global Coalition of over 66 partners committed to defeating Daesh. The Global Coalition is committed to tackling the threat posed by foreign terrorist fighters travelling to the region to join Daesh or travelling from Daesh-held territories to other countries. The Counter-Daesh Coalition Working Group on Foreign Terrorist Fighters, co-led by the Netherlands, Turkey and the United States, is working with Coalition partners to implement the obligations and recommendations in UN Security Council Resolution 2178 on 24 September 2014. This resolution requires countries to take steps to counter foreign terrorist fighters, to expand current obligations under international law, and to strengthen international measures that prevent suspected foreign terrorist fighters from travelling, disrupt financial support to foreign terrorist fighters, and further strengthen international and regional co-operation mechanisms.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577512/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-14T09:55:04.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577512/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577512/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-07","Libya: Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the international community is taking to prevent Daesh fighters in Libya fleeing into neighbouring countries.","false","Biography information for Rehman Chishti","Gillingham and Rainham","Rehman Chishti","45375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577513","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-14","<p>Daesh are under significant pressure in Sirte. I welcome the positive steps the Libyan people are taking to remove Daesh from their country, including Prime Minister Serraj’s recent request for precision airstrikes from the United States of America against Daesh. The defeat of Daesh in Libya will have a positive impact on the long term stability of Libya and the region. But other extremist groups, including those with links to Al Qaeda, remain a threat to the country and the region. It is important that the International Community fully supports the Government of National Accord in their efforts to bring all legitimate military and security forces under a unified command. This will help to restore stability, seal the defeat of Daesh and close the space in which the terrorists and criminal gangs are operating.</p><p>It is vital that the international community is relentless in its efforts to ensure Daesh and its affiliates are defeated wherever they arise, including tackling those fighters who remain in Libya. The UK is playing a leading role in the Global Coalition of over 66 partners committed to defeating Daesh. The Global Coalition is committed to tackling the threat posed by foreign terrorist fighters travelling to the region to join Daesh or travelling from Daesh-held territories to other countries.</p><p>It is also important to consider what comes after the defeat of Daesh, in areas that they control. We are working closely with the new Libyan government and international partners to develop a comprehensive approach to stabilisation and post-conflict reconstruction, including through the £10m UK CSSF allocation.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577513/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-14T09:57:23.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577513/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577513/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-07","Libya: Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the strength of Daesh in Libya after its defeat in Sirte.","false","Biography information for Rehman Chishti","Gillingham and Rainham","Rehman Chishti","45376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577514","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-16","<p>On 8 September, a joint session of the Upper and Lower Chambers of the Uzbek Parliament appointed Prime Minister Shavkat Mirziyoev as Acting President of Uzbekistan and tasked the Central Electoral Commission to organise Presidential elections. The Central Electoral Commission has since announced that these will take place on 4 December.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577514/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T13:58:14.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577514/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577514/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-07","Uzbekistan: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on the future leadership of Uzbekistan following the death of President Karimov.","false","Biography information for Rehman Chishti","Gillingham and Rainham","Rehman Chishti","45377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577515","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>We are concerned by the reports of an attack on Sebastian Kolowa Memorial University and officials in our embassy in Tanzania are following up with the Tanzanian authorities.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577515/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-12T15:45:42.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577515/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577515/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-07","Tanzania: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations to his Tanzanian counterpart on steps to prosecute those responsible for the recent attack on the Sebastian Kolowa Memorial University in Lushoto.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","45339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577516","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>The UK actively engages with members of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC), including the United Arab Emirates, Kuwait, Qatar and Saudi Arabia, on humanitarian and development assistance. The Gulf States are not signatories to the UN Refugee Convention of 1951, and there is no legal refugee status in these countries. However, the Gulf States continue to contribute generously to humanitarian support for the Syria crisis and we recognise and welcome the substantial contribution made by Gulf states to the humanitarian aid response for Syria and the numbers of Syrians already in the Gulf. The Gulf states are now home to almost one million Syrians, and have pledged more than $3 billion in humanitarian assistance. Kuwait co-hosted the London Donor Conference in February 2016 where Gulf states pledged $739 million.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577516/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-12T13:55:33.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577516/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577516/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-07","Middle East and North Africa: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what information he holds on how many people fleeing persecution or extreme violence in (a) the Middle East and (b) North Africa have been offered temporary residence and respite in (a) the United Arab Emirates, (b) Kuwait, (c) Qatar and (d) Saudi Arabia in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","45340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577517","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>As and when candidate countries have met the requirements for accession in full, it will be for those countries and European Union members at the time to decide on membership. That point remains some way off.</p><p>The UK remains committed to driving reform, embedding stability and addressing shared challenges such as security and migration in the Western Balkans and Turkey. The UK will continue to support countries committed to the accession process in meeting the necessary requirements.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577517/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-12T15:08:35.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577517/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577517/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-07","Turkey: EU Accession","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the Government's policy is on Turkey's accession to the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","45349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577518","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>We remain concerned about the cases of Ali Mohammed al-Nimr, Dawood al-Marhoon and Abdallah al-Zaher and continue to follow them closely. The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson) raised concerns with the Saudi Arabian Foreign Minister Al-Jubeir during their meeting on 7 September. Our expectation remains that they will not be executed. Our Embassy in Riyadh also frequently raise our concerns.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577518/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-12T13:59:06.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577518/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577518/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-07","Saudi Arabia: Capital Punishment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to the government of Saudi Arabia on the cases of Ali Mohammed al-Nimr, Abdullah al-Zaher and Dawood al-Marhoon.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","45557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577519","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-16","<p>The Government is aware of the recommendations of the Committee of the Elimination of Racial Discrimination in respect to the resettlement of Chagossians. Ratification of the Convention has not been extended to the British Indian Ocean Territory and such questions remain outside the remit of the Committee. The Government remains committed to its review of current policy on resettlement and will continue to keep Parliament, Chagossians and their supporters closely informed of progress on the issue.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577519/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T13:26:29.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577519/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577519/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-07","Ilois: Resettlement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he plans to take in respect of the recommendations in paragraph 41 of the UN Committee on the Elimination of Racial Discrimination's concluding observations on the 21st to 23rd periodic report, published on 26 August 2016, on facilitating the resettlement of the Chagossians.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","45523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577520","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-09-12","<p>The UK Government has frank discussions with the Government of Bahrain about human rights concerns both in public and in private. We urge the Bahraini authorities to respect the rights of all its citizens, and call on them to protect the universal rights of freedom of expression. The former Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) spoke to the Bahraini Foreign Minister, Sheikh Khalid Bin Ahmad Al Khalifa on 14 June about his case. An official from our Embassy in Bahrain has attended all his hearings to date, including most recently on 5 September. We will continue to monitor his case closely and raise concerns with the Government of Bahrain.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577520/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-12T13:57:16.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577520/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577520/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-09-07","Nabeel Rajab","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to the government of Bahrain on the case of Nabeel Rajab in that country.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","45526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577521","Department of Health","false","2016-09-12","<p>The previous Minister of State for Health, Alistair Burt, met with the interim Chairman of Southern Health Trust on 16 May and 7 June. There are no current plans for any further meetings. NHS Improvement oversees NHS trusts and foundation trusts, and is accountable to the Department for this work and its other functions.</p>","South West Surrey","Mr Jeremy Hunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577521/answer",,,,,"45540 ; 45542","2016-09-12T08:29:38.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577521/answer","Biography information for Mr Jeremy Hunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577521/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-07","Southern Health NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what mechanisms of accountability his Department has used when working with the Southern Health Trust.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","45541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577522","Department of Health","false","2016-09-15","<p>Published data on finished admission episodes with a primary diagnosis of malnutrition for 2015-16 are not yet available. We do not hold data on the number of people admitted to hospital with malnutrition. Hospital Episode Statistics record admissions to hospital rather the number of patients, as a person may have more than one admission within a certain period.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577522/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-15T14:37:59.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577522/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577522/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-07","Malnutrition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people were admitted to hospital with malnutrition in England in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","45529"
