Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many complaints have been made to the DVLA about vehicle excise duty refunds in each month since October 2014.","false","Biography information for Alistair Burt","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","45517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577639","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-14","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) does not hold information in this way.</p><p> </p><p>Since 1 October 2014, vehicle excise duty (VED) automatically ends when the DVLA receives notification that a vehicle has been sold to a new keeper or the motor trade. VED also ends when DVLA is notified that a Statutory Off Road Notification has been made or a vehicle has been stolen, exported or scrapped. When the DVLA record is updated with one of these qualifying events, a refund is usually generated automatically to the registered keeper. This can take longer in a small number of cases where further enquiries by the DVLA are necessary or the vehicle keeper is asked to provide additional information.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577639/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-14T14:54:04.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577639/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577639/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-07","Motor Vehicles: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many refunds of vehicle excise duty were awarded (a) less than four weeks,(b) between four and six weeks and (c) more than six weeks after the original claim being made.","false","Biography information for Alistair Burt","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","45518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577640","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-14","<p>The following table sets out the volume of refunds of vehicle excise duty issued in each financial year since 2014.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016/17*</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>4,439,033</p></td><td><p>5,477,955</p></td><td><p>2,234,931</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>*</strong><strong>Figures for 2016/17 are April to August</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577640/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-14T14:57:38.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577640/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577640/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-07","Motor Vehicles: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many refunds of vehicle excise duty have been awarded in each financial year since 2014.","false","Biography information for Alistair Burt","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","45519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577641","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-16","<p>English local authorities have a wide range of powers under the Road Traffic Regulation Act 1984 to prohibit or restrict parking throughout the day or at specific times and by specific types of vehicles on any length of the highway, including bus stops. These powers enable local authorities to create bus stop clearways prohibiting all vehicles, other than buses, from stopping at bus stops. Over 90% of English local authorities have the power under Part 6 of the Traffic Management Act 2004 to enforce bus stop prohibitions/restrictions.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577641/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T11:01:18.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577641/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577641/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-07","Parking Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what powers are available to local authorities and what enforcement action can local authorities take to prevent cars parking at public bus stops.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","45472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577642","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Department is aiming to launch its consultation in late Autumn 2016. A specific date is still to be decided.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577642/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-12T14:07:24.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577642/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577642/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-07","Severn River Crossing: Public Consultation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when his Department plans to launch its consultation on the future of the Severn Bridges.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","45450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577643","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-14","<p>Driver licensing is a devolved matter in Northern Ireland. Fees for all driver licence transactions in Northern Ireland are a matter for the Department for Infrastructure.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577643/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-14T14:07:47.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577643/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577643/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-07","Driving: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the reasons are for the difference in cost between professional driving licences issued in Northern Ireland and Great Britain; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","45488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577644","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-14","<p>The UK’s airports and airlines operate in the private sector and it is therefore for airlines operating at Heathrow and Gatwick to determine their schedules, working in conjunction with the airports’ operators.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577644/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-14T14:03:55.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577644/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577644/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-07","London Airports: Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions his Department has had with Gatwick and Heathrow airports to ensure that international flights are staggered to prevent congestion at immigration desks.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","45477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577645","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-12","<p>Following the EU Referendum on 23 June the Government is considering the impacts of the decision to leave the EU, and are now preparing to negotiate our exit. Until this happens we remain a member state of the EU with all of the rights and obligations that this entails.</p><p> </p><p>In accordance with this the Department is therefore considering how it can best ensure that we will be able to implement the EU Weights and Dimensions Directive (2015/719).</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577645/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-12T15:53:49.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577645/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577645/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-07","Large Goods Vehicles: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans the UK has to enact the EU Weights and Dimensions Directive (2015/719); and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","45409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577646","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-16","<p>I sent a response to the hon. Member for Walsall North on this issue on 13<sup>th</sup> September 2016.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577646/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T11:11:14.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577646/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577646/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-07","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to respond to the letter from the hon. Member for Walsall North of 8 August 2016 on homes and the adoption of private roads.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","45354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577647","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-12","<p>Speed cameras on all-purpose trunk roads are already yellow in colour. 41 camera sites on the motorway network have been converted from grey to yellow. Of these, 39 sites contain speed cameras. There is an ongoing programme to convert all the camera sites on the motorways from grey to yellow.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577647/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-12T14:03:00.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577647/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577647/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-07","Speed Limits: Cameras","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 5 February 2016 to Question 25499, how many individual speed cameras on the strategic road network have been converted from grey paint to yellow paint; and how many camera sites contain such cameras.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","45389"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577648","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-14","<p>The reported time of an incident to Her Majesty’s Coastguard is the time a 999 call is received. Whilst HM Coastguard specifically records the reported time of an incident it does not specifically record an actioned time when that action does not involve the tasking of a search and rescue resource, such as when Coastguards are gathering information.</p><p> </p><p>Information may be held within the text narrative of an incident record but this would require a check of tens of thousands of records over the last five years at disproportionate cost to the taxpayer.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577648/answer",,,,,"45362","2016-09-14T14:38:32.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577648/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577648/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-07","Rescue Services: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the average time taken was from when a call was received for the coastguard service to when that call was actioned in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","45363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577649","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-14","<p>The reported time of an incident to Her Majesty’s Coastguard is the time a 999 call is received. Whilst HM Coastguard specifically records the reported time of an incident it does not specifically record an actioned time when that action does not involve the tasking of a search and rescue resource, such as when Coastguards are gathering information.</p><p> </p><p>Information may be held within the text narrative of an incident record but this would require a check of tens of thousands of records over the last five years at disproportionate cost to the taxpayer.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577649/answer",,,,,"45363","2016-09-14T14:38:31.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577649/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577649/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-07","Rescue Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the reported time of an incident to the coastguard service is the time a 999 call is received or the time that incident is raised on the computer.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","45362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577650","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-12","<p>The new Franchise Agreement will require that Clacton-on-Sea station is equipped with digital Customer Information System (CIS) screens, help points and CCTV cameras linked back to a central control centre. Passengers at Clacton-on-Sea will also benefit from free of charge improved network bandwidth WiFi at the station by 2018. Abellio shall undertake a refurbishment programme at Clacton-on-Sea. This will include a deep clean of the station.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577650/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-12T16:24:20.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577650/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577650/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-07","Clacton-on-Sea Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with Abellio Greater Anglia on commitments for station upgrades at Clacton-on-Sea, as part of the new franchise agreed in August 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","45352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577653","Women and Equalities","false","2016-09-15","<p>The Government is dedicated to improving the lives of transgender people and ensuring that barriers to their success are removed from society.</p><p> </p><p>This is reflected in the Government response to the Women and Equality Select Committee inquiry into transgender equality, where we set out a range of initiatives to improve the lives of transgender people. This includes improving the way people are supported by gender identity services through new training of NHS staff. The Government response can be accessed at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/transgender-equality-report-government-response" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/transgender-equality-report-government-response</a>.</p><p> </p><p>This is not the only work we have delivered. In November 2015, the Government issued ‘Providing services for transgender customers: a guide’, which set out advice for all service providers to ensure that transgender people are welcomed, included and valued as customers, clients, users or members, and that they are treated fairly and appropriately. This can be accessed at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/providing-services-for-transgender-customers-a-guide" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/providing-services-for-transgender-customers-a-guide</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Alongside those initiatives, the Government will continue to push forward action to tackle transgender inequality and improve services for transgender people.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577653/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-15T17:31:37.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577653/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577653/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-09-07","Gender Recognition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what steps the Government is taking to (a) ensure that support services for transgender people are made more accessible and localised and (b) enhance existing transgender support services.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","45470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577654","Women and Equalities","false","2016-09-13","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that transgender people are free from discrimination, including in the provision of facilities and services. In Department for Education buildings, transgender people are therefore free to use the toilets that match the gender with which they identify.</p><p> </p><p>There are also twelve accessible toilet facilities in Sanctuary Buildings, London and six in Piccadilly Gate, Manchester, which are gender neutral. In line with the Government Equalities Office publication “Recruiting and Retaining Transgender staff – a guide for employers”, which suggests that departments should consider introducing gender neutral toilets when carrying out refurbishments or introducing new toilets into their buildings, gender-neutral toilet facilities will also be provided at the Department’s future London office at the Old Admiralty Buildings.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577654/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-13T16:59:58.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577654/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577654/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-09-07","Government Equalities Office: Sanitation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what toilet facilities there are for transgender people at the Government Equalities Office at (a) the Sanctuaries Building, London and (b) Piccadilly Gate, Manchester.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","45458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577655","Women and Equalities","false","2016-09-15","<p>According to the latest data from the Office for National Statistics:</p><p>(a) In 2015, a total of 861 civil partnerships were formed in England and Wales.</p><p>(b) 7,732 couples in England and Wales converted their existing civil partnership into a marriage between 10 December 2014 and 30 June 2015.</p><p>(c) A total of 7,366 marriages were formed in England and Wales between same sex couples between 29 March 2014 (when the legislation came into effect) and 30 June 2015.</p><p>This information is available online at: <a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/birthsdeathsandmarriages" target="_blank">http://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/birthsdeathsandmarriages</a>.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577655/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-15T17:38:35.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577655/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577655/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-09-07","Civil Partnerships and Marriage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, how many (a) civil partnerships, (b) conversions of civil partnerships into marriages and (c) same sex marriages have taken place since 10 December 2014.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","45544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577656","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>Information on EU citizenship is not held by the Department for Work and Pensions, its agencies or its non-departmental public bodies.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577656/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-12T14:19:47.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577656/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577656/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-07","Department for Work and Pensions: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many citizens of other EU countries work in his Department, its agencies and non-departmental public bodies.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","45511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577657","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Rural Affairs and Biosecurity, Lord Gardiner, replied to the letter of 3 August from hon. Member for Walsall North on 12 September.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577657/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-12T12:08:23.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577657/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577657/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-09-07","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when she plans to respond to the letter from the hon. Member for Walsall North of 3 August 2016 on legislation on dangerous dogs related to a constituency case.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","45353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577660","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>DWP takes its responsibilities to protect the privacy of customers and their data very seriously. This is reflected in its published Personal Information Charter. In the event of a security or information breach, the DWP would always ensure that it fulfils its obligations under the Data Protection Act and from the Information Commissioner’s Office to notify any affected persons as soon as it is possible to identify them.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577660/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-12T16:43:09.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577660/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577660/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-07","Department for Work and Pensions: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what his Department's policy is on informing benefit claimants of breaches of security in his Department which may compromise their data.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","45410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577661","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions apologises for the delay in responding. We have been investigating the issues raised by your constituent and a response has sent to the hon. Member for Walsall North, Mr David Winnick, today.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577661/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-12T13:12:05.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577661/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577661/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-07","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when his Department plans to respond to the letter from the hon. Member for Walsall North of 1 August 2016 to the Benefits Director on pension credit related to a constituency case.","false","Biography information for Mr David Winnick","Walsall North","Mr David Winnick","45357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577662","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-12","<p>Ministers in DWP and DCLG have met and continue to meet with stakeholders representing local authorities, supported accommodation, refuges, commissioners, and all categories of supported housing providers, be they charities, housing associations, voluntary organisations or from the commercial sector.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State has confirmed that the Government expects to make an announcement on the way forward for supported housing in early autumn.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577662/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-12T13:58:01.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577662/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577662/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-09-07","Refuges: Local Housing Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what representations he has received from women's refuges on the local housing allowance cap; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","45406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577663","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-12","<p>Business rates are based on valuations from the Valuation Office Agency and we do not intervene in their independent assessments. We will look closely at the impacts of the forthcoming revaluation and consult on how to make sure the right support is in place for ratepayers to adjust to any changes.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577663/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-12T15:48:17.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577663/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577663/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-09-07","Schools: Solar Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what representations he has received from schools with solar panel installations on the proposed change in business rates for such installations from 2017; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","45405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577664","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-19","<p>We publish statistics on numbers of solar photovoltaic installations rather than on the number of solar panels installed or whether installations are domestic or small business. Typically installations on domestic properties will be less than 4 kiloWatts in capacity, and those on small businesses between 4 and 50 kiloWatts in capacity. The number of <em>installations</em> within each of these capacity bands over the last three years for which statistics are available is as follows:</p><p> </p><p><strong><em>Number of installations</em></strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong> 2013 </strong></p></td><td><p><strong> 2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> 2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>0-4 kW – largely domestic</em></p></td><td><p>97,327</p></td><td><p>131,994</p></td><td><p>179,066</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>4-50 kW – largely small businesses</em></p></td><td><p>8,086</p></td><td><p>9,041</p></td><td><p>12,254</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><em>Source data:</em></p><p><em><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/solar-photovoltaics-deployment" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/solar-photovoltaics-deployment</a> (table 1)</em></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577664/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-19T09:46:01.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577664/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577664/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-07","Solar Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the number of solar panels installed in homes and small businesses in the UK in each of the last three years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","45437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577665","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-27","<p>In the last 12 months Innovate UK has committed £13.4 million from its programmes to support business‑led innovation in Northern Ireland and works closely with the Northern Ireland Executive to encourage innovation.</p><p> </p><p>Innovate UK is strengthening the way it connects businesses with knowledge, partners and opportunities and is increasing its regional presence to further develop its joined‑up innovation support network for business. It is establishing a team of regional managers and is in the process of recruiting a regional manager to be based in Northern Ireland, co-located with Invest NI.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577665/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-27T07:29:40.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577665/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577665/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577665/answer/previousversion/11061","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-07","Innovate UK: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps Innovate UK has taken in the last 12 months to assist businesses in Northern Ireland build sustainable economic growth.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","45342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577666","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-19","<p>The Department of Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy has not received any requests for documents submitted to the European Commission for State aid clearance with regard to plans to support radioactive waste and decommissioning proposals for new nuclear power stations.</p><p>The former Department of Energy and Climate Change (DECC) received one such request in the last 12 months. The request asked for “the main document setting out the United Kingdom justification for state aid clearance, along with a full list of the titles of all support documents, submitted to the European Commission, in respect of the European Commission consideration of the pricing methodology for waste transfer contracts to be concluded between the UK Government and operators of new nuclear power plants and its compatibility with EU state aid rules, on which the Commission reported its conclusions on 9 October 2015”.</p><p>In its response DECC confirmed that it did hold the information requested but was withholding it as the information fell within the scope of the exception set out in regulation 12(5)(a) of the Environmental Information Regulations and that the public interest lay in withholding the information.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577666/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-19T09:41:14.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577666/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577666/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-07","Nuclear Power Stations: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what Freedom of Information requests (a) his Department and (b) the Department for Energy and Climate Change received in the last 12 months in respect of requests for documents submitted to the European Commission in support of the UK case of State Aid Clearance for plans to support radioactive waste and decommissioning proposals for new nuclear power stations; what response his Department provided to those requests; and what the reasons were for each such response.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","45466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577667","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-23","<p>The survey has been renamed the BEIS Energy and Climate Change Public Attitudes Tracker Survey. The next quarterly results from the survey will be released on 27 Oct 2016 and made available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/public-attitudes-tracking-survey" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/public-attitudes-tracking-survey</a>.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577667/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-23T13:34:00.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577667/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577667/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-07","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Surveys","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans he has for the Department of Energy and Climate Change's Public Attitudes Tracking Survey.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","45465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577669","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-16","<p>The focus on a proper industrial strategy provides a once in generation chance to embrace the opportunities of our new global role and upgrade our economy so it works for everyone. We will work with the breadth of British industry, local leaders, innovators, employees and consumers to create the conditions for future success across the UK.</p><p>The economic recovery of recent years means that our economy is better able to withstand the challenges of exiting the European Union. Our industrial strategy will support and encourage companies to trade internationally, create a business environment that will attract overseas investors to locate for the long term and identify and maximise the opportunities from leaving the European Union.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577669/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T10:50:43.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577669/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577669/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-07","Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to prepare an industrial strategy as a result of the UK's decision to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","45498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577670","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-16","<p>The industry-led Space Innovation and Growth Strategy set out that space services and applications are likely to provide the majority of future growth in the sector. Maritime surveillance and satellite broadband were highlighted in this strategy as priority growth opportunities, and the UK Space Agency has been working with industry to remove barriers to growth and develop specific opportunities in these areas.</p><p>In 2013, Innovate UK established the Satellite Applications Catapult specifically to help UK industry to develop applications and services based on space data and grasp these new opportunities. The UK Space Agency’s Space for Smarter Government Programme works across Government to promote the intelligent use of space data. An outcome from that programme is the use of satellite broadband to support the NHS’s mobile breast-cancer screening services.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577670/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T13:55:54.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577670/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577670/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-07","Satellites","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to encourage companies to capitalise on markets that make use of satellite data, such as maritime surveillance and satellite broadband.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","45496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577671","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-14","<p>On 31 August 2016, my noble Friend the Minister of State for Energy and Intellectual Property, together with my rt. hon. Friend the Chief Secretary to the Treasury, met with members of the senior teams from the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority and Sellafield Limited to discuss the challenges of decommissioning the Sellafield site safely and securely. On 1 September 2016, they visited the Sellafield site to see first-hand the work that the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority (NDA) is doing to manage the civil nuclear legacy safely, securely and responsibly, and saw a number of the resilience and emergency preparedness enhancements which have been made to the legacy ponds and silos.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577671/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-14T16:29:42.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577671/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577671/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577671/answer/previousversion/10833","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-07","Sellafield: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent discussions he has had with the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority and Sellafield Ltd on safety performance at Sellafield.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","45455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577672","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-14","<p>We have not made a projection of domestic solar’s contribution to UK energy use.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577672/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-14T16:25:24.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577672/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577672/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577672/answer/previousversion/10827","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-07","Housing: Solar Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of UK energy use which will be from domestic solar production in each of the next five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","45457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577673","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-14","<p>They are answerable to an independent regulator – the Office for Nuclear Regulation (ONR), which sets the standards by which the UK nuclear industry must operate.</p><p>We have a strong regulatory system across all nuclear operators in the UK. The ONR operates in line with international standards and the requirements set by the International Atomic Energy Authority (IAEA).</p><p>The ONR operates transparently and provides its assessment of standards at nuclear sites in its Annual Report and Accounts, which is laid in Parliament every year. In the latest report, the Chief Nuclear Inspector concluded that nuclear sites have satisfactorily achieved high standards of safety and security, thereby protecting the workforce and the public from harm.</p><p>The ONR’s Annual Report and Account sets out in some detail the ONR’s regulatory strategy at Sellafield, which is designed to enable Sellafield Limited to deliver its remediation programmes to reduce hazard and risk on the site, with a particular focus on accelerating safe and secure retrievals from the legacy ponds and silos. The ONR reports that this strategy is helping to secure “evidence-based confidence that the licensee is complying with its statutory obligations and that workers and the public are protected from the hazards of the site”.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577673/answer",,,,,"45454","2016-09-14T16:26:14.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577673/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577673/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577673/answer/previousversion/10829","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-07","Sellafield: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will make an assessment of compliance of operations at Sellafield with regulatory safety standards.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","45453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577674","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-14","<p>They are answerable to an independent regulator – the Office for Nuclear Regulation (ONR), which sets the standards by which the UK nuclear industry must operate.</p><p>We have a strong regulatory system across all nuclear operators in the UK. The ONR operates in line with international standards and the requirements set by the International Atomic Energy Authority (IAEA).</p><p>The ONR operates transparently and provides its assessment of standards at nuclear sites in its Annual Report and Accounts, which is laid in Parliament every year. In the latest report, the Chief Nuclear Inspector concluded that nuclear sites have satisfactorily achieved high standards of safety and security, thereby protecting the workforce and the public from harm.</p><p>The ONR’s Annual Report and Account sets out in some detail the ONR’s regulatory strategy at Sellafield, which is designed to enable Sellafield Limited to deliver its remediation programmes to reduce hazard and risk on the site, with a particular focus on accelerating safe and secure retrievals from the legacy ponds and silos. The ONR reports that this strategy is helping to secure “evidence-based confidence that the licensee is complying with its statutory obligations and that workers and the public are protected from the hazards of the site”.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577674/answer",,,,,"45453","2016-09-14T16:26:14.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577674/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577674/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577674/answer/previousversion/10832","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-07","Office for Nuclear Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of safety standards set by the Office of Nuclear Regulation.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","45454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577675","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-19","<p>The Government committed in its manifesto to reduce the burden of regulation on business by £10bn through a Business Impact Target. The first report on the Business Impact Target was published in June and showed that we have so far delivered £885 million of deregulation savings against it.</p><p>The Government will carefully consider the implications of leaving the European Union for the Business Impact Target, and the opportunities to further reduce burdens on business.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577675/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-19T14:34:37.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577675/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577675/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-07","Business: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the potential opportunities to reduce the regulatory burdens on business (a) before and (b) after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","45444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577676","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-11","<p>It is for the regulator, Ofgem, to regulate the industry to ensure consumer receive accurate bills.</p><p>Following the publication of an open letter by Ofgem, the trade association Energy UK has estimated that 11,000 customers (less than 0.05% of the total 23 million gas accounts in the UK) were charged the wrong amount for their gas usage, owing to the incorrect recording of imperial and metric meters.</p><p>Customers affected by these errors will not have to take any action and will be contacted directly by their supplier, who will repay any overcharging (including an appropriate interest payment). Energy suppliers will not seek repayment from those customers who have been undercharged and where, appropriate, could offer support to financially vulnerable customers to ease the transition to accurate bills.</p><p>The Ofgem open letter is available online at: www.ofgem.gov.uk/publications-and-updates/open-letter-gas-suppliers-metricimperial-indicator-charging-error</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577676/answer",,,,,,"2016-10-11T13:01:24.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577676/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577676/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-07","Natural Gas: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if the Government will press companies to set up compensation schemes to be used in the event that they overcharge customers as a result of inaccurate gas readings.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","45545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577677","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-19","<p>The Department recognises a need to understand the risks and benefits associated with underground coal gasification better. It commissioned a report from the consultancy WS Atkins Plc into the greenhouse gas implications of underground coal gasification. This report will be received in due course.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577677/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-19T09:42:51.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577677/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577677/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-07","Coal Gasification: Greenhouse Gas Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to the Answer of 20 October 2015 to Question 11541, whether the Department for Energy and Climate Change completed its assessment of the greenhouse gas emissions related to underground coal gasification.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","45531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577678","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-16","<p>The Government is examining the case for commercial spaceflight and launching small satellites from both runway-based spaceports and a vertical launch spaceport. The UK Space Agency is working with the Department for Transport to draft legislation that will enable both horizontal, sub-orbital and vertical launch spaceflight operations from the UK as part of the Modern Transport Bill.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577678/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T13:55:24.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577678/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577678/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-07","Space Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he plans for the proposed UK spaceport to have vertical launch capacity.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","45522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577679","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-15","<p>The costs of setting up the new Department are ongoing and the processes will take some time to complete. The Department will provide a breakdown of costs once the transition period is complete.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577679/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-15T13:25:01.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577679/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577679/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577679/answer/previousversion/11481","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-07","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will publish a breakdown of the costs incurred in the creation of his Department.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","45581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577680","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-16","<p>The Government’s intent to grow the UK’s Space sector was set out most recently in our National Space Policy, which we published in 2015. The UK Space Agency deploys a broad range of mechanisms, working with other delivery partners such as Innovate UK, Local Economic Partnerships, the European Space Agency and the Satellite Applications Catapult, to encourage investment in British Space companies. These measures include working closely with industry to identify and remove regulatory barriers to growth, investing in innovative technology needed to enter new space markets and building the national facilities essential to develop the UK’s future space products. We have also set up the structures needed to drive investment and growth, for example, the UK Space Gateway at Harwell in Oxfordshire. The UK Space Agency also works closely with the Department for International Trade to secure overseas inward investment and develop export opportunities for the space industry.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577680/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T13:58:48.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577680/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577680/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-07","Space Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to encourage investment in British space and satellite companies.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","45521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577681","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-14","<p>Through the offshore oil and gas licensing approval regime the Oil and Gas Authority considers a range of factors when awarding licences to the operators of offshore oil and gas fields, including ownership, technical competence and financial stability. The Government has also announced it will be introducing tighter controls on ownership of critical infrastructure to ensure the full implications of foreign ownership are scrutinised.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577681/answer",,,,,,"2016-10-14T13:56:20.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577681/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577681/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-09-07","Offshore Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of foreign state ownership of North Sea drillings rigs on the UK's energy security.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","45546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577682","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-16","<p>The government continues to promote regional trade growth across the UK, and has recently established the new Department for International Trade to promote the UK’s exports and trade and drive inward investment. As ever, we remain open to opportunities to promote growth across the UK and encourage further international trade and investment.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577682/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T09:32:44.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577682/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577682/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-09-07","World Expo","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential effect on regional trade growth in the UK of hosting the 2025 World Expo.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","45560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577683","Department for International Trade","false","2016-09-14","<p>There has been no expenditure incurred by the Department for International Trade to date beyond the legacy Departments’ Spending Review allocations.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577683/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-14T14:25:08.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577683/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577683/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-09-07","Department for International Trade: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, if he will publish a breakdown of the costs incurred in the creation of his Department.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","45580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577684","Department for International Trade","false","2016-09-16","<p>My rt hon. Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade has been accompanied by departmental officials on all foreign visits.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577684/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T11:38:19.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577684/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577684/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-09-07","Department for International Trade: Visits Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, who has accompanied him on each of his foreign visits in his official ministerial capacity since the establishment of his Department.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","45359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577685","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-12","<p>The Prime Minister will lead our negotiations for leaving the EU. We are about to begin these negotiations and it would be wrong to set out further internal positions in advance. As we prepare for negotiations on the UK’s exit from the EU, the Government will continue to consult with a broad range of stakeholders in order to secure the best possible deal for the whole UK.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577685/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-12T15:37:36.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577685/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577685/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-09-07","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether he plans for the Minister for Universities and Science to be part of the Government's team negotiating exit from the EU.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","45381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577686","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-14","<p><strong>There has been no change to the rights and status of EU nationals in the UK, or of British citizens in the EU, as a result of the referendum. The Department for Exiting the European Union is assessing the skills needed for the department, the right security protocols, and relative merits of potential employees in line with usual practice. </strong></p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577686/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-14T16:01:57.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577686/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577686/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-09-07","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of employing nationals of other EU member states in his Department.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","45403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577687","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-14","<p><strong>The new Department for Exiting the European Union is properly resourced. Detailed work is underway to establish the final budget required and this will be voted on and published as part of the Supplementary Estimate process. </strong></p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577687/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-14T16:07:05.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577687/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577687/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-09-07","Department for Exiting the European Union: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, if he will publish a breakdown of the costs incurred in the creation of his Department.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","45582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577898","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-20","<p>The Office of Rail and Road’s comments on open access competition were in-line with the Competition and Markets Authority’s (CMA’s) report on passenger rail services published on 8 March 2016. In their report the CMA did not envisage their options for greater open access competition would come into effect before 2023 at the earliest. The Government responded to the report in a written ministerial statement on 17 March 2016, explaining that we would explore options for potentially implementing the CMA’s recommendations.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is actively considering ‎the CMA's recommendations, in discussion with industry stakeholders. Until this process is further developed, and the options fully considered, the Government is not in a position to provide an assessment of the timing for potential reforms in this area.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577898/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-20T14:53:01.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577898/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577898/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-09-07","Railways: Competition","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the timing proposed by the Office of Road and Rail on opening all main Inter City Railway lines to an open-access competition, in the light of the fact that there is no financial measurement of the consequences of such a competition on the East Coast Main Line including the impact on the existing Virgin Trains East Coast franchise.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradshaw",,"Lord Bradshaw","HL1646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577899","Department of Health","false","2016-09-16","<p>The Department’s National Institute for Health Research is funding the Health Protection Research Unit in Health Impacts of Environmental Hazards, whose remit includes air pollution research. This unit is a partnership between King’s College London and Public Health England in collaboration with Imperial College London.</p><p> </p><p>The Research Councils, funded by the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, invest in a range of research into the health impacts of air pollution exposure in the United Kingdom and internationally. They also support research into the sources and processes controlling air pollution and how it can be better monitored and mitigated to inform integrated policies across health, the natural and built environments, transport and energy.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577899/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-16T11:06:32.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577899/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577899/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-09-07","Air Pollution","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the recent research findings that magnetite, derived from pollution, can damage the brain, what further research they are funding into the health risks of air pollution.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL1647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577900","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-09-19","<p>Air quality has improved significantly in recent decades and we are working at local, national and international levels to continue those improvements. The UK currently meets legal limits for almost all pollutants.</p><p> </p><p>The national air quality plan for NO<sub>2</sub>, published in December last year, combines targeted local and national measures, forming part of a wider approach that exploits new and clean technologies, such as electric and ultra-low emission vehicles. As part of the national plan we are requiring five cities to implement Clean Air Zones. The relevant cities are Birmingham, Derby, Leeds, Nottingham and Southampton.</p><p>These measures will also reduce particulate matter concentrations.</p><p> </p><p>Alongside national action, local authorities have opportunities to improve air quality for the protection of public health and the environment through their decisions on local land use planning, environmental health, roads, highways and local air quality management. Local authorities are also able to introduce Clean Air Zones voluntarily.</p><p> </p><p>The Committee on the Medical Effects of Air Pollution provides independent evidence to Government on the impacts of air pollution on health. It regularly reviews latest research, and Defra reflects its guidance in its policy-making.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577900/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-19T15:20:39.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577900/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577900/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-09-07","Air Pollution","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the recently introduced air quality action plans will require local authorities to take into account the latest research showing that air pollution particles can enter the nervous system and the brain.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL1648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577901","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-09-21","The Government remains committed to putting in place a well-managed Blue Belt to protect precious marine habitats and species. We are aiming for the third tranche of Marine Conservation Zones to be comprehensive and complete our contribution to the ecologically coherent network of Marine Protected Areas in the North East Atlantic. This network plays an important part in helping stem the decline of marine habitats and species and in aiding their recovery. The Government has also committed to doubling the size of protected ocean around the UK Overseas Territories to four million square kilometres. This commitment included the immediate formal designation of Marine Protected Areas around the Pitcairn Islands and St Helena which will help protect the Territories’ important endemic marine species.",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577901/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-21T14:52:39.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577901/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577901/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-09-07","Marine Conservation Zones","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, when designating the third tranche of Marine Conservation Zones, whether they will take into account the Wildlife and Countryside Link’s Marine Charter, and in particular its call to address current gaps in Marine Protected Areas, stem the decline in marine habitats, and recover those that are damaged.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL1649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577902","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-09-21","On 3 September 2016 the Government announced plans to ban the sale and manufacture of cosmetics and personal care products containing microbeads which cause harm to the marine environment. Our plans will be informed by a formal consultation later this year. At the same time, evidence will be gathered on the extent of the environmental impacts of microbeads found in other products, including those for domestic use, before considering what more can be done in future to tackle other plastics which affect the marine environment.",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577902/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-21T14:50:38.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577902/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577902/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-09-07","Microplastics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the proposed ban on microbeads in cosmetics, whether they are considering an outright ban on their use in all other domestic products.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL1650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577903","Home Office","false","2016-09-21","<p>Cycling on the pavement is an offence under Section 72 of the Highways Act 1835 and illegal cycling on pavements causes much concern especially to our most vulnerable pedestrians, such as elderly, disabled and visually impaired people.</p><p>The number of offenders sentenced to a fine at all courts for offences related to cycling, in England and Wales, from 2010/11 to the period from April to December 2015 can be viewed in the attached table on fines for cycling offences. Data for 2016, including finalised data for Quarter 1, is planned for publication in May 2017. It is not possible to establish whether or not an indictable offence involved a cyclist without checking case files at the courts concerned. This can only be done at disproportionate cost.</p><p>The Home Office collects data on the number of fixed penalty notices issued for motoring offences only and these data are published by the Home Office in the annual ‘Police Powers and Procedures’ publication. Data on fixed penalty notices issued to cyclists are not held centrally.</p><p>This Government supports any action taken by the police to deter and reduce the number of cycling offences. The enforcement of the offence of cycling on the pavement is an operational matter for Chief Officers of police, as determined locally and based on local priorities.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577903/answer","PQ HL1651 HL1652 table on fines for cycling offences.xls","PQ HL1651 HL1652 table on fines for cycling offences.xls","PQ HL1651/HL1652 - Table","PQ HL1651/HL1652 - Table","HL1652","2016-09-21T15:02:15.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577903/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577903/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-07","Cycling: Road Traffic Offences","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many cyclists were fined or issued with fixed penalty notices for (1) summary offences, or (2) more serious offences, in (1) 2010–11, (2) 2011–12, (3) 2012–13, (4) 2013–14, (5) 2014–15, and (6) 2015–16.","false","Biography information for Baroness McIntosh of Pickering",,"Baroness McIntosh of Pickering","HL1651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577904","Home Office","false","2016-09-21","<p>Cycling on the pavement is an offence under Section 72 of the Highways Act 1835 and illegal cycling on pavements causes much concern especially to our most vulnerable pedestrians, such as elderly, disabled and visually impaired people.</p><p>The number of offenders sentenced to a fine at all courts for offences related to cycling, in England and Wales, from 2010/11 to the period from April to December 2015 can be viewed in the attached table on fines for cycling offences. Data for 2016, including finalised data for Quarter 1, is planned for publication in May 2017. It is not possible to establish whether or not an indictable offence involved a cyclist without checking case files at the courts concerned. This can only be done at disproportionate cost.</p><p>The Home Office collects data on the number of fixed penalty notices issued for motoring offences only and these data are published by the Home Office in the annual ‘Police Powers and Procedures’ publication. Data on fixed penalty notices issued to cyclists are not held centrally.</p><p>This Government supports any action taken by the police to deter and reduce the number of cycling offences. The enforcement of the offence of cycling on the pavement is an operational matter for Chief Officers of police, as determined locally and based on local priorities.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577904/answer","PQ HL1651 HL1652 table on fines for cycling offences.xls","PQ HL1651 HL1652 table on fines for cycling offences.xls","PQ HL1651/HL1652 - Table","PQ HL1651/HL1652 - Table","HL1651","2016-09-21T15:02:15.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577904/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577904/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-09-07","Cycling: Pedestrian Areas","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to reduce incidents of cyclists mounting and cycling on pavements.","false","Biography information for Baroness McIntosh of Pickering",,"Baroness McIntosh of Pickering","HL1652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577905","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-21","<p>There has been no change to the rights and status of British citizens in the EU, or EU citizens in the UK, as a result of the referendum.</p><p>The Prime Minister has been clear that during negotiations she wants to protect the status of EU nationals already living here, and the only circumstances in which that would not be possible is if British citizens’ rights in European member states were not protected in return.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577905/answer",,,,,,"2016-09-21T12:15:36.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577905/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577905/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-09-07","British Nationals Abroad: EU Countries","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to protect the rights of British citizens living in the EU set out in the EU Charter of Fundamental Rights.","false","Biography information for Lord Steel of Aikwood",,"Lord Steel of Aikwood","HL1653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577906","Department for International Development","false","2016-09-16","<p>The UK Government is determined to improve sexual and reproductive health and rights, including access to modern family planning methods. We were instrumental in ensuring the Sustainable Development Goals included two targets covering universal access to sexual and reproductive health and reproductive rights and we are encouraging other countries to increase their commitments. Our investments in family planning aim to reach 24 million additional women and girls by 2020 and we are on track to meet this. In 2014, the most recent year for which figures are available, UK spending on family planning was £203 million, exceeding our 2012 London Summit commitment to double our yearly spend in this area.</p><p>We are currently developing our plans to 2020. As well as a large commitment to the United Nations Population Fund Supplies Programme (£356m until 2020), DFID also supports the Family Planning 2020 Secretariat, work on shaping reproductive health markets through the Clinton Health Access Initiative, and the Reproductive Health Supplies Coalition.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577906/answer",,,,,"HL1655 ; HL1656 ; HL1657","2016-09-16T11:00:42.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577906/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/577906/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-09-07","Developing Countries: Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what funding the Department for International Development is making available for family planning and sexual and reproductive health and rights this year.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL1654"
